<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Presidents Saluted at Convention  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Up in front of another Republican
convention, but only on video this time, Ronald Reagan was saying
anew in Berlin, ''Mr. Gorbachev, tear down this wall.'' It was part
of Tuesday night's tribute to former GOP presidents Reagan, Bush
and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, Bush and their wives took the kudos in person. Former
first lady Nancy Reagan came on behalf of her husband, who is
suffering from Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   On a night billed as full of patriotism and ''a lot of
emotion,'' the presidential video tributes affirmed Reagan's
ability to move a crowd, even in his absence, even with words that
are old.
</P>
<P>
   Tears rolled down the cheeks of Bill Campbell, 65, a former
state Senate Republican leader in California who was elected the
same year Reagan was elected governor in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was fantastic,'' Campbell said, apologizing for the catch
in his voice. ''He's a fantastic man and it's a great tragedy, the
Alzheimer's getting him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fine memories are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan video began with the 1981 assassination attempt and a
narrator intoning ''We almost lost him.'' It continued with clips
of Reagan speaking after the explosion of the space shuttle
Challenger and the famed quote at the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lusty cheers rose from the crowd. Indeed, they cheered and
applauded repeatedly during the six-minute Reagan video.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan, in a pale green dress and large pearls, stood to
acknowledge the ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's video began with a narration of America's war with Iraq
and included the former president talking about his son, Gov.
George W. Bush, who will accept the party's presidential nomination
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think George's record can stand all the scrutiny in the
world. I think it will show a man of honor, a man of integrity,''
the former president says in the tape.
</P>
<P>
   As the band played ''Devil with a Blue Dress,'' Barbara Bush
took the stage with a very blue dress indeed, with polka dots, and
introduced her son, appearing by satellite from nearby Gettysburg,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope I am the first person to welcome you to Philadelphia,
the city of motherly love,'' she said, a twist on the ''brotherly''
love for which the city likes to be known.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush tribute ended with the father reading an August 1998
letter written to sons George W. and Jeb, the governors of Texas
and Florida. In the letter he talks about how instances may arise
where the sons may have to disagree with some of his policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't worry about it,'' the former president says in the
letter. ''Nothing can ever be written that will drive a wedge
between us, nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was praised as the president who ''put America back
together in his quiet, steady way'' after Watergate. The video also
told of the Ford family's personal struggles and included clips
from Betty Ford's surgery for breast cancer. It ended with Ford
talking about what George W. Bush can do for America.
</P>
<P>
   Seized with emotion, Ford's eyes welled with tears during his
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Ford, told C-SPAN that this would be his and his wife
Betty's last political convention and described it as a
''concluding appearance to indicate our support.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to be there because we feel so strongly about the
Republican philosophy, the record of the Republican party over the
years, and our two candidates George W. and Dick Cheney,'' said
Ford, who is 87.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, in an interview with CNN's Larry King, said Bush was
''running this campaign better than the one run by his father a
couple of years ago. George has learned from the mistakes that were
made in the last Bush campaign and so far I think they're producing
good results.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan is 89, former President Bush, 76.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0000 </TRAILER>
