<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO To Release Tobacco Ind. Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Health Organization is accusing the
tobacco industry of secretly trying to undermine its campaign to
reduce smoking around the world, according to The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   A WHO report to be released Wednesday details a sophisticated
effort to pit other U.N.-affiliated agencies against WHO
initiatives, as well as using statements from scientists who have
financial ties to the tobacco industry, the Post reported on its
Web site Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said former Food and Drug Administration
Commissioner David Kessler was one of the report's authors and much
of the information is culled from tobacco company documents that
came to light through court proceedings against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tobacco companies' own documents show that they viewed
WHO, an international public health agency, as one of the foremost
enemies,'' the Post quoted the report as saying. ''The documents
show further that the tobacco companies instigated global
strategies to discredit and impede WHO's ability to carry out its
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Post, the report explains the ways the industry
created and used ''ostensibly independent quasi-academic, public
policy and business organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   David Davies, a vice president with Philip Morris International,
did not deny to the Post that the industry used these tactics, but
said that it no longer used them.
</P>
<P>
   The company documents are ''the product of a polarized and
unproductive environment in which few solutions were sought, and
conflict prevailed over consensus,'' Davies told the Post. ''Phlip
Morris regrets this.''
</P>
<P>
   The report highlights a 1988 meeting in Boca Raton, Fla., where
tobacco executives allegedly planned their attack.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Boca Raton plan, the report says, ''is a master
plan for, among many goals, attacking WHO's tobacco control
programs, influencing the priorities of WHO Regional Offices, and
targeting the structure, management and resources of the WHO.'' The
plan ''identified 26 global threats to the tobacco industry and
multiple strategies for countering each,'' the report says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
