<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Pundits Left Hanging in Philly  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wipe that smile off your face!
</P>
<P>
   This remained the hope and even advice of many TV pundits
Tuesday, as the sweetness-and-light of the Republican National
Convention shined on.
</P>
<P>
   CNN political analyst William Schneider spoke for many restless
commentators, watching the GOP gathering in Philadelphia, when he
said, ''How long can this convention go on with its happy face?
Sooner or later, the delegates are going to want some red meat.
Where's the beef?''
</P>
<P>
   At his side, analyst Jeff Greenfield chimed in, ''Forget the
media's indignation over image-making.'' The real problem, he
posed, may be that making ''audiences feel warm and gooey isn't
smart politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the Republicans weren't listening as they propelled
George W. Bush toward his nomination Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even reporters' attempts to escalate the feud between former
President Bush and President Clinton went nowhere. Bush declined to
enlarge on his outburst on NBC Monday night that if Clinton didn't
stop attacking his son, he would say what he felt about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been very good about not criticizing the president for
eight years,'' Bush said Tuesday, refusing to be goaded into
breaking his silence.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching at straws? Fox News Channel panelists couldn't help
chuckling at news that members of the Texas delegation planned to
bow their heads in silent protest during the speech of Arizona
congressman Jim Kolbe, the only openly gay GOP member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is probably the most controversial thing that will happen
all week,'' said correspondent Mara Liasson, smiling. ''As a
journalist, I am grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's made-for-TV program had its moments:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ret. Army Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf addressing the convention by
satellite from the deck of the USS New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nancy Reagan stoically watching the video tribute to her
husband, former President Reagan, now stricken with Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   -- Soon-to-be candidate Bush making another ''reminder''
appearance by satellite, this time from Gettysburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   For a second day, broadcast's PBS and cable's CNN, Fox News
Channel, MSNBC and C-SPAN stayed with the Philadelphia story.
Broadcast networks ABC, CBS and NBC joined the action only at 10
p.m. EDT -- for the latter two networks, within their newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps NBC's decision to skip the convention altogether Monday
night was justified. Its rerun of the drama ''Third Watch'' drew 10
million viewers, while the CBS newsmagazine ''48 Hours,'' which
devoted roughly half the broadcast to the Republicans, attracted
6.4 million viewers. ABC, which stayed with the convention for the
full hour, was watched by 5.9 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   National ratings for the cable networks put CNN predictably in
first place, with 1.2 million viewers between 8 and 11 p.m. EDT.
During the same period, Fox News Channel averaged 676,000 viewers.
MSNBC brought up the rear with 516,000 viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Why, in a three-way face-off, would MSNBC come in third? After
all, its coverage was staffed by NBC News' first string (including
Tom Brokaw and Tim Russert) and heavily promoted on its broadcast
sister, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the question, MSNBC spokesman Mark O'Connor said,
''We are very happy with this number.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is double what we normally do on an average week in July,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe MSNBC would have fared better without its
heat-and-no-light analysts James Carville and Bill Bennett.
Democratic strategist Carville, as usual, was a hopped-up
rattletrap while conservative activist Bennett mostly sat by
looking dyspeptic.
</P>
<P>
   Their segments alone were good reason to switch channels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0006 </TRAILER>
