<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former penny stock mogul Brennan arrested on bankruptcy fraud charges </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - For disgraced financier Robert E. Brennan,
the knock on the door came while he was showering, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agents arrived with warrants about 6:30 a.m.
Tuesday at his apartment on the Colts Neck property where he once
had his archly named Due Process Stables.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in two decades of continuing clashes with
stock regulators, Brennan faced criminal charges and was placed in
handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two indictments unsealed with his arrest charge that Brennan
attempted to hide from creditors over $500,000 he got from cashing
casino chips less than a month after he filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the one-time penny stock mogul made two court
appearances dressed in a blue Oxford shirt and blue jeans - and
wrist shackles - instead of the dark suits he favors for courthouse
garb.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 56, became publicly known in the 1980s through his
television commercials for his former flagship brokerage, First
Jersey Securities Inc., stepping off a helicopter and urging
viewers to ''come grow with us.''
</P>
<P>
   After sitting through a state court bail hearing in Freehold in
the morning, silent except to answer a few routine questions,
Brennan spoke at length during his bail hearing in Newark on the
federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to defend this case,'' Brennan told U.S.
Magistrate Stanley R. Chesler. ''I don't intend to go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Chesler found that Brennan posed ''some risk of
flight'' and ordered him to remain under house arrest in Colts Neck
until he could post $500,000 cash or secured bail. He allowed
Brennan to travel to Florida and New York, but not by private
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Brennan had posted $250,000 cash bail set by state
Superior Court Judge Theodore J. Labrecque Jr., but was kept in
federal custody and taken to the hearing before Chesler.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Michael Critchley said Brennan's friends were
helping him, but declined to say who posted his bail.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy State Attorney General Thomas R. Clark had argued in the
state proceeding that Brennan posed a flight risk and sought $1
million bail. He noted that Brennan has regularly flown overseas on
private aircraft and still has access to $6 million in an overseas
trust fund that he has not surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Similar arguments were made at the federal hearing by Assistant
U.S. Attorney Henry E. Klingeman, who sought $1 million bail and
house arrest in the Colts Neck apartment, in a gated community at
the Due Process golf course, now to be auctioned to satisfy
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan rose and broke his silence, asserting he has no control
over the trust and is not a beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was created when I was enormously solvent for the benefit
of others,'' said Brennan, a native New Jerseyan who said his
official residence is in Juno Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The five-count state indictment charged that Brennan failed to
declare money from the casino chips and a $5,900 wagering account
he maintained with the New York Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   The six-count federal indictment accused him of making false
statements in his bankruptcy case regarding the chips.
</P>
<P>
   He is to enter a plea on the federal charges Thursday, and to
the state charges on Sept. 11. His lawyer, Michael Critchley, said
he would plead innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan has been barred from the securities industry for years,
but now faces the possibility of prison for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The state indictment includes second-degree charges that carry a
penalty of up to 10 years in prison. Each of the six federal
charges carries a penalty of up to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   However, Critchley estimated that the likely state term, if
convicted, would be about seven years, making Brennan eligible for
parole in 14 months. Klingeman said the likely federal term would
be 27-30 months, with no parole.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not indicate which case would be tried first,
but Critchley said that since the cases stem from the same facts,
double jeopardy protection barred more than one trial.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the chips was raised earlier this year by state
prosecutors in a civil proceeding. Brennan responded then that the
matter had been ''examined in minutia'' four years ago and was only
raised ''to smear and embarrass me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, authorities revealed more about the transaction,
charging that Brennan cashed $504,794 in chips at 2:40 a.m. Sept.
4, 1995, less than a month after declaring bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He then walked off with a duffel bag full of cash,'' First
Assistant Attorney General Paul Zoubek said at a Trenton news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Outside federal court, Critchley did not dispute that the
transaction occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I'm saying was that those chips were not assembled on
prior trips,'' as prosecutors charge, Critchley said.
</P>
<P>
   The state raised the issue of whether Brennan was improperly
shielding assets to keep them from being used to satisfy the $45
million he agreed to pay to aggrieved investors.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan has paid very little of the $45 million, which was set
in a June 1999 deal with New Jersey regulators to settle their
stock fraud lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan denied wrongdoing, but consented to a finding that he
used ''substantial influence'' at two brokerages to make
''unreasonably excessive profits'' in stocks in which he held an
undisclosed interest from 1988-95.
</P>
<P>
   The state had charged that after closing First Jersey in the
late 1980s, Brennan secretly controlled two other brokerages to
push low-cost, high-risk stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Securities and Exchange Commission maintains that
First Jersey engaged in similar behavior by subjecting potential
investors to high-pressure sales tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan avoided serious sanctions until 1995, when a federal
judge in Manhattan ruled that Brennan had cheated investors and
ordered him to pay what is now more than $78 million for the agency
to give back to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan filed for bankruptcy protection in Trenton federal court
on Aug. 7, 1995, just before the money was due.
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered a series of legal setbacks since then, but court
records indicate he managed to maintain a lavish lifestyle. He flew
around the world and dined graciously as part of his job to attract
members to the golf club.
</P>
<P>
   However, he did have to relinquish his control of two race
tracks and leave the governing board of his alma mater, Seton Hall
University, on which he served as chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
