<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens, Taylor Agree On Contract  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Wide receiver Travis Taylor, the 10th pick in
the NFL draft, agreed in principle to a five-year, $10.9 million
contract with the Baltimore Ravens on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the second of the Ravens' two first-round picks, is
expected to report to training camp Thursday morning. His holdout
began last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A standout at the University of Florida, Taylor will sign a
contract that includes a guaranteed $5 million signing bonus.
According to Taylor's agent, Steve Weinberg, the bonus is 33
percent higher than that received by Baltimore cornerback Chris
McAlister, last year's No. 10 overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   ''Travis is very happy to put this behind him,'' Weinberg said
in a telephone interview. ''This is a huge deal for Travis. He can
provide for his family for a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal came after an intense round of negotiations that began
Sunday night. According to a source familiar with the talks, the
contract will pay Taylor $1 million more than the Ravens offered a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens insisted that their initial offer was slotted between
the ninth and 11th picks, but Weinberg said otherwise. After
further negotiations, an agreement was finally reached.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously we're pleased and relieved to have it done,'' coach
Brian Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   Billick said Taylor would not play in the Ravens' first
preseason game Saturday against the Philadelphia Eagles at PSINet
Stadium. He also wasn't sure if Taylor would play the following
preseason game, Aug. 12, against the New York Jets at PSINet
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Billick said Taylor would probably be held out of both games not
as a punishment, but as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ''You need two weeks to prepare a team, individually and
collectively, to play a preseason game in order for them to stay
healthy and be able to handle themselves properly so that you can
get anything out of it,'' Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who caught 34 passes for 463 yards and six touchdowns at
Florida last season before declaring for the draft as a junior, was
projected to be the Ravens' third receiver. But Billick said that
scenario would be ''very ambitious'' for the early part of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens are thin at receiver due to injuries to starter
Patrick Johnson (broken right clavicle) and reserve Kendrick Nord
(broken right fibula).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0014 </TRAILER>
