<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Salutes Bush at Convention  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- On an evening honoring sacrifice and
service, John McCain smartly saluted George W. Bush on Tuesday at
the Republican National Convention, beckoning independents and
Democrats to support the Texas governor as a man of ''courage and
character.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him,''
said McCain, deferring to his one-time rival from the very podium
where Bush will accept the presidential nomination on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you believe that patriotism is more than a soundbite and
public service should be more than a photo-op, then vote for
Governor Bush,'' said McCain, who spent more than five years in a
North Vietnamese prison camp. The Arizonan won seven primaries last
winter on a message of political reform, and showed strong appeal
among independent voters who could be pivotal in the campaign for
the White House this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That made him a strategic choice as closing speaker of the
second night of the convention -- a program designed to broaden
Bush's political appeal as well as stress his support for a
muscular military and to stir memories of Republican presidents of
the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight night, Bush addressed the delegates from
the campaign trail. They cheered when his image appeared on huge
screens scattered throughout the hall, and again when he pledged to
''rebuild our military and strengthen our alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   But they sent up the loudest cheers of the convention thus far
for a video tribute to Ronald Reagan, the conservative icon who
twice led the party to victory and is suffering from Alzheimer's
Disease at 89.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the campaign quickened on Day 2 of the Bush-Cheney
convention. So, too, the pace outside. Four miles from the
convention hall, police arrested at least 280 protesters in the
first serious demonstrations of the convention week.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner John Timoney said his bicycle was used as a
weapon against him, adding, ''I've got a few bumps and bruises but
I'm OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have taken the streets,'' said Sue Kelly, 54, of Richmond,
Va., protesting the death penalty. ''We just don't like Republicans
and what the ruling class stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke from Gettysburg, Pa., near the famous Civil War
battlefield, where he returned McCain's compliments, saying his
'straight talk and strong convictions are admired across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also introduced Condoleezza Rice, his national security
adviser who served his father in the White House. ''It all begins
with integrity in the Oval Office,'' said Rice. ''George W. Bush is
a man of his word. Friend and foe will know that he tells the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   A black woman, Ms. Rice was a bridge between Monday night's
convention program that stressed diversity, and the Tuesday script
that underscored the need for a strong defense.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf also was on the program, giving
a stern partisan speech from the USS New Jersey, docked in Camden,
N.J., where it will become a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the party's 1996 nominee, stirred the GOP delegates
with a tribute to fellow World War II veterans as ordinary
Americans who became heroes of liberty. He asked all veterans in
the convention hall to stand to the cadence of their military
anthems.
</P>
<P>
   There were video tributes to the three living former Republican
presidents: Gerald R. Ford; Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Bush had VIP seats in the hall and in a poignant
appearance, Nancy Reagan left her husband's side to represent him
among the former presidents.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, the nation's 41st president, delivered a father's
proud endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think George's record can stand all the scrutiny in the
world,'' the former president said of his son in one video. ''I
think it will show a man of honor, a man of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, visited the convention hall
during the day to check the podium where he will deliver his
acceptance speech Wednesday evening. So, too McCain, accompanied by
his wife Cindy, who recorded the scene on a hand-held videocamera.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Stowell Jr., doctor from Royalston, Mass., voted for
McCain in the nominating roll call, to send a message on campaign
finance reform. ''I hope my little thing sends a message to
Governor Bush that he should be talking about this. We want him to
be elected but we want him to be elected talking about campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-speech interview with reporters, McCain said he was
dismayed by all the perks that wealthy donors are heaping on
delegates and GOP officeholders in connection with the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The system's broken; we are addicted to soft money,'' McCain
said. He quickly noted that the problem is not just Republican.
''The fact is it's a bipartisan issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He made no overt mention of his signature campaign issue in his
prepared speech.
</P>
<P>
   He touched on themes he raised in his campaign last winter, then
said the same concerns drew him to Bush's side.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you believe America deserves leaders with a purpose more
than expediency and opportunity, then vote for Governor Bush,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is easy to forget in politics where principle ends and
selfishness begins. It takes leaders of courage and character to
remember the difference,'' he said. ''Tomorrow, our party will
nominate such a leader.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''I say to all Americans, Republican, Democrat or
independent, if you believe America deserves leaders with a purpose
more ennobling than expediency and opportunism, then vote for Gov.
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the son and grandson of admirals and a prisoner of war
in Vietnam, noted that many years ago Bush's father had served
under McCain's grandfather in World War II. ''Now it is my turn to
serve under the son of my grandfather's brave subordinate,'' he
said. ''I am proud to do so for I know that by supporting George W.
Bush I serve my country well.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pappageorge, an alternate from Michigan, set the political
context for the appearance by McCain, who attracted votes from
independents and some Democrats in his bid for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have to do is find out who all those people were who
crossed over and get them to cross over again,'' said Pappageorge,
who said he voted for the Arizona senator in last winter's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday evening's program was a more conventional one for
Republicans, who scripted an opening night show on Monday that was
devoted to diversity and the desirability of racial inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats dispatched two black members of the House -- Reps.
Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas and Harold Ford of Tennessee -- to
ridicule GOP claims on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   They said GOP rhetoric is not matched by the party's record on
issues ranging from civil rights to display of the Confederate
flag. ''You can't overlook their record,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Bush said, ''I agree with Colin Powell
that Republicans need to do more to reach out to minorities. And I
agree with him that I'm the man to do it for the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has generally refrained from mentioning either President
Clinton or Vice President Al Gore by name, but he did so twice
during the day. Once came at a rally in Charleston, W.Va., the
other aboard his campaign plane.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father stepped in, as well, irritated because Clinton
suggested the governor was in the running because his ''daddy was
president.''
</P>
<P>
   If the criticism persists, the former president said, he'll tell
Americans what he really thinks about Clinton ''as a human being
and as a person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0020 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0013 </DOCNO>
