<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Ship Holds Canada Military Gear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A cargo ship has anchored off Newfoundland and its
American owners have refused to deliver its load of Canadian
military gear until they are paid the money they say they are owed.
</P>
<P>
   Two Canadian warships, the destroyer HMCS Athabaskan and the
frigate HMCS Montreal were close by the cargo boat, the GTS Katie,
and the Defense Ministry said Tuesday it was weighing its options.
</P>
<P>
   The American owner of the Katie has decided ''he's not going to
move,'' Defense Department spokesman Alastair Mullin said. The ship
dropped anchor about 80 miles off the southeast tip of Newfoundland
island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the situation of unresolved contractual obligations
we have no intention of raising the anchor until we have some kind
of resolution,'' Peter Margan, president of ship owner Third Ocean
Marine Navigation of Maryland, told CTV news.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was carrying 500 military vehicles -- including tanks
and armored personnel carriers -- and tons of other equipment. It
was contracted to bring the equipment back from Kosovo, where it
was deployed with Canadian peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Three Canadian soldiers assigned to guard the cargo have spent
the last two weeks on board the ship watching videos and waiting
for settlement of the contract dispute between the shipowner and
Andromeda Navigation of Montreal, which chartered the ship.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer from Andromeda, which was contracted by the government
to get the equipment back to Canada, said the company was trying to
resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But so far it ''has spent over $850,000 of its own money to
bring the cargo to Canada and it hasn't received a cent yet from
the government,'' George Pollack told CTV news. Third Ocean says it
is still awaiting payment from Andromeda.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money in dispute was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The Katie was due in Montreal in mid-July, but it has been
circling in the Atlantic for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department routinely charters foreign-flag ships and
aircraft to haul equipment overseas. The navy has no transports
equipped to carry heavy armor and the air force's C-130 Hercules
transports are limited to about 20 tons of cargo.
</P>
</TEXT>
