<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Step Into Philly's Crowd and Listen  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Pictures tell part of the story: a parade
across the podium; cheering crowds; red, white and blue everywhere.
Each person has another tale to tell. This week, the Republican
convention city is swarming with people, ideas, arguments. Step
into the downtown crush. Here's what some delegates, protesters and
workers have to say:
</P>
<P>
THE FAITHFUL
</P>
<P>
   ''People are looking for answers,'' says Debe McGuire. She's in
Philadelphia to offer a few. Here's her husband, Jim: ''Go back to
some of the things our fathers and mothers taught us about honesty
and sincerity.'' The two accountants are from northeast Texas -- as
if the straw cowboy hats didn't tell you -- and their political
views are in plain sight. ''Dubya'' buttons. The message ''The LIFE
of the party'' splashed across their backs. She's an alternate
delegate who helped start a local Christian Coalition chapter. The
McGuires are here to speak their minds and make sure the party
listens. ''Washington needs to hear from the people back home,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
THE FUND-RAISER
</P>
<P>
   When other children got dragged to museums, Jim Cox was off to
election rallies. His mom had the bug. Turned out it was
hereditary. ''I was hooked from an early age,'' says the
31-year-old Internet fund-raiser from Virginia. ''To me, the
neatest thing is to see people debate an issue.'' He's here
working, helping candidates raise money. But he's also here because
he loves it -- and as founder of a political action committee for
young Republicans. ''Regardless of where you fall on the
ideological spectrum, one of the most important things you need to
do as an American citizen is vote.''
</P>
<P>
THE SHORT-ORDER COOK
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Fearon serves up home-cooked meals at the Down Home
Diner, not political insights. The convention? ''So far, I think
it's OK for the city, it's doing a lot of business for the city,''
says the 39-year-old cook who adopted Philadelphia as his hometown
after emigrating from Jamaica. He's registered to vote, and will be
back at the polls again this year, though none of the candidates
have him very excited. George W. Bush? ''I believe he's a nice
guy.'' Still, he'd prefer to just stick with the status quo. ''I
just feel comfortable with Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
THE PACIFISTS
</P>
<P>
   Ruth and Ralph Johnson can teach these young protesters a few
things. She remembers marching against the Vietnam War, though the
exact year escapes her. ''Nixon was in the White House,'' she says.
The two are Quakers, both retired in their early 70s, but nowhere
near taking it easy. ''We are very upset,'' she says, and here's
why: military spending, the failed drug war, health care problems
and too many guns. And neither the Republicans or the Democrats do
anything substantial to fix it, they say. ''That's why (the voters)
stay home,'' says Ruth. ''They say 'ho-hum,''' says Ralph,
finishing the thought. The two came from Delaware to march and have
their say. But they made sure to stop for the Sunday meeting of
Friends in Philadelphia. Their prayer? ''A new millennium of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
THE CHAIRWOMAN
</P>
<P>
   ''People are getting turned off by politics. It might be the age
of specialization. They're so busy out doing their thing,'' says
Barbara Marumoto, one of Hawaii's few Republican legislators and
her delegation's chairwoman. A pen behind her ear, an armful of
books in her hand and a pocket full of surfboard logos (her son
sells them), she also balances political hopes with reality. Her
state tends to go Democratic, but Marumoto, a 22-year veteran of
the state House, says this year might be different. As the
granddaughter of Japanese immigrants, here's her reason: ''Bush's
message of welcoming legal immigrants in the country will resonate
very well in Hawaii,'' she says. ''He realizes the value and the
contributions of different ethnic groups.''
</P>
<P>
   This threesome of 20-year-olds from Haverford College doesn't
feel too welcome here. Carrying a poster calling for the release of
a convicted cop-killer doesn't go over too well at a gathering of
the GOP faithful. But Jared Tankel, Neal Kronley and Brady
McCartney are committed. ''It really shines a lot of light on what
we're doing -- which is the state murdering people,'' says Kronley.
The three take the bus in each day to protest. They also hoped to
see the sights, but their poster got them thrown out of a public
exhibition hall downtown, they said. ''A lot of these people don't
really want to listen,'' Tankel says. ''We're kind of putting it in
their faces so that they're forced to look at it and at least read
it.''
</P>
<P>
THE ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Lala Babin is 12 and dreams of Broadway. But politics is fun,
too: ''I like history, so I was excited when my mom told me that I
could come here.'' She's in the spirit -- sporting plastic beads
that blink red, white and blue; a towering hat of red, white and
blue a la Cat-in-the-Hat; glittering glasses that read ''2000.''
Her mom's an alternate from Texas (they live in ''a weed'' of a
town just over the line from Louisiana) and her friends were a bit
jealous of her trip -- though not all of them get the point. ''Some
of my friends don't even know what Republicans and Democrats are.''
Though acting calls her, she's already dabbled in politics. Last
summer she was elected chief of one of the two tribes at her summer
camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0125 </TRAILER>
