<HEADLINE> Gay Congressman Talks About Trade  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe never strayed from
his free-trade theme in a three-minute speech to the Republican
National Convention and conservative GOP delegates, bowing to the
greater theme of party harmony, offered only mild, silent protest
to the GOP's only openly gay member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Republicans hailed the speech as an important sign of a thaw
in their party's relations with homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   But several members of the Texas delegation took off their
cowboy hats and bowed their heads in prayer as a silent protest
during Kolbe's speech. One held up a sign proclaiming, ''There is a
way out.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe there are moral rights and wrongs and we also
believe that if any one of us did wrong, we would want others to
pray for us,'' said Butch Davis of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the audience listened politely and gave Kolbe mild
applause.
</P>
<P>
   The current Republican platform opposes gay marriages, declares
''homosexuality is incompatible with military service'' and says
''we do not believe sexual preference should be given special legal
protection or standing in law.'' What's important, gay Republicans
say, is that Bush has not been so unfriendly.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not perfect, but he's someone I respect and he's not a
mean-spirited bigot,'' said Washington, D.C., delegate David
Catania, a gay city councilman.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe, 58, acknowledged being gay in 1996, but has not been a
vocal advocate for gay rights in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   This year 18 delegates and alternates to the convention are
openly gay, compared to five in 1996, said Kevin Ivers, a spokesman
for the Log Cabin Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
