<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Market for a Steam Locomotive?  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEARNY, N.J. (AP) -- Fancy a locomotive?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you can snap up the one-of-a-kind Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio No.
614 for at least $1 million. The owner will even throw in two
auxiliary cars for free.
</P>
<P>
   But rail buffs and model train lovers take note: This little
beauty isn't going to fit under your kid's Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   It's an 890,000-pound, 112-foot long, fully functional steam
locomotive that can reach speeds of 125 mph. It's got enough muscle
to pull an Amtrak train.
</P>
<P>
   The train, one of the last steam passenger locomotives built in
the United States, is being sold because its owner plans a new
tourist railroad in Canada with bridges that can't support the
weight of old No. 614.
</P>
<P>
   An auction last month at the NJ Transit's Meadows Maintenance
Facility drew a high bid of only $200,000. But owner Ross Rowland
Jr. rejected the offer, saying his train is worth between $1
million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   With such a hefty price tag, the average rail buff won't be able
to afford it. It's been offered to Microsoft founder Bill Gates,
Wall Street whiz Warren Buffett, and actor Kevin Costner -- all
acknowledged train fanciers -- but they haven't bitten.
</P>
<P>
   So bids from anyone interested will be considered, auctioneer
David Barnhardt said Tuesday. If a suitable deal can't be struck at
a future auction, Barnhardt said, Rowland will donate the engine to
a rail museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the last mainline steam engine built in North America
in 1948, as railroads were transitioning from steam to diesel,''
said Rowland, who has owned No. 614 since 1979, when he bought it
from the CSX railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been thoroughly refurbished and updated, and it's the
only steam locomotive in North America that has all the equipment
and appliances you'd need to pull an Amtrak train.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is the only steam engine ever leased by Amtrak,
having pulled ''The Cardinal'' through West Virginia at speeds
approaching 80 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowland bought it, he oversaw a crew of 15 mechanics and
more than 100 volunteers who completely rebuilt the locomotive. It
took 18 months and $1.5 million to bring No. 614 up to snuff; it
can now pull a 25-car passenger train all day without having to
stop for service.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has been a train nut ever since he was a kid. Yes, he
said, he had a set of Lionel toy trains when he was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I quickly grew tired of those, and wanted the big ones,
the real ones,'' he said. ''I've been in love with trains ever
since I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Anderson, who maintains trains for the New York City Transit
Authority, stopped by the July 15 auction to take a peek at some
living history.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the last of its type,'' he said. ''I've seen it go on a
lot of excursions, and I just wanted to see it one last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland appreciates the thought -- he loves the romance of the
rails.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without the steam engine, there would have been no westward
expansion,'' he said. ''It enabled the industrial revolution and
the population of the western two-thirds of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Combine that with the sights and sounds of a steam engine as
it passes by you -- the hiss of the steam, the sound of the whistle,
the way the ground shakes underneath you -- and it's almost an alive
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   DFB&AMP;A Auctions:
http://www.trains-trams-trolleys.com/auctions.html
</P>
<P>
   Iron Horse Enterprises: http://www.chessie614.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0136 </TRAILER>
