<DOCNO> APW20000802.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Cuts Sharing Convention Stage  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- ''Render unto Caesar, but let the people
keep their own.''
</P>
<P>
   These words, on page five of the Republican national platform,
reflect how central tax cuts have always been to the party's
agenda. But in the GOP's drive to broaden its appeal, tax relief's
place in the spotlight at the Republican National Convention is
being crowded out by other priorities such as improving education
and attracting minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a different pitch now,'' said former Rep. Bob Livingston
of Louisiana. ''The same principles, but a different pitch. It's
not as shrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Little was said from the podium about tax cuts during the
convention's first two days, despite the rush by Republicans in
Congress to pass bills beforehand to eliminate the tax penalty on
marriage, repeal inheritance taxes and cut taxes on Social Security
benefits. All these have drawn veto threats from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the relative silence is part of a GOP effort to
avoid frightening people concerned that deep tax cuts could eat up
a projected budget surplus before it even arrives in Washington,
siphoning off money for crucial government programs while mainly
helping the wealthiest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't want to say anything at all,'' said Joe Andrews,
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ''America rightly
sees the Democrats as the party of fiscal discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Republicans will continue to deliver a tax-cutting
message, but in a soft-focus way: Wednesday night, a single mom, a
computer company president and a family farmer will join Virginia
Gov. Jim Gilmore in helping describe the GOP's tax relief vision.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to pair education and taxes. It's important to
recognize that education is the key,'' Gilmore said in an
interview. ''But it is important to make the point that tax cuts
really relate to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore said the Democratic charges of draining the surplus is
''the old way of the old Democrats. They try to set one priority
against the other and force you to make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, nominee-in-waiting George W. Bush has proposed major tax
cuts that would total roughly $1 trillion over the next decade and
they are a staple of most Republican congressional campaigns.
Although cutting taxes may not play as well for a national
election, the issue still energizes the GOP base and could be a
deciding factor in some districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been overtaxed for two or three years,'' said Mike
Weber, a delegate from Reno, Nev. ''There are whole piles of money
and the first thing the Democrats want to do with it is spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only GOP political figures to dwell at length on tax
cuts during the first two days of the convention were the 29
congressional candidates who spoke during Monday's little-noticed
afternoon session.
</P>
<P>
   ''When George W. Bush is in the White House the American people
will have the tax relief they deserve,'' said Sen. Rod Grams of
Minnesota, who is seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   With the budget surplus so large, Vice President Al Gore is also
proposing tax cuts, but they would apply only to people with middle
incomes and are intended to help with specific things such as child
care and the costs of caring for elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   To Republicans, this tack is a Democratic attempt to use the tax
code to redistribute income from the rich to the poor without
advocating creation of costly new government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to use if for social engineering. They want to
cajole you,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. ''We
don't pick winners and losers in the tax code. ''
</P>
<P>
   Armey and Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., have been traveling the
country holding mock ''debates'' to push for scrapping the tax code
and replacing it with either a flat income or sales tax. They held
the 38th of these debates Tuesday night in an auditorium outside
the convention hall, with an audience of young GOP volunteers and
little media attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0147 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
