<DOCNO> APW20000802.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Going Upbeat Has a Price  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- They didn't ask. He didn't tell. And hardly
anyone listened.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the second-tier speakers at the Republican National
Convention. Even openly gay Republican Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe,
speaking to a party with an anti-gay rights platform and some
delegates who didn't want him there, couldn't keep the crowd's
attention with his talk about trade.
</P>
<P>
   In a convention thin by design on attacks against Democrat Al
Gore, firing up the troops is proving a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Headliners Tuesday night such as Sen. John McCain and Bob and
Elizabeth Dole went over moderately well, but the audience only
really came to life for the music and when a video was shown of
Ronald Reagan, one of three ex-presidents honored.
</P>
<P>
   Others gamely plugged along.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt IV, great-grandson of one of the party's
favorite presidents, a leader regarded as father of the national
parks, spoke about conservation and the ''senseless killing of
pelicans.''
</P>
<P>
   He told a long story in his few minutes about a Florida farmer
who persuaded President Roosevelt to help protect his pelican
breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cry went out: 'Are you for pelicans or progress?''' the
great grandson said. ''As it turned out, the American people were
for pelicans.''
</P>
<P>
   There was much chattering and schmoozing and even a bit of
newspaper reading on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, Ave Marie Bie, head of the Wisconsin Public
Service Commission, complained about the lack of national energy
policy and won some applause when she said motorists are being
''Gored'' at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is largely a target untouched in the
convention's main events so far, and Gore has been getting off
lightly, too. George W. Bush's campaign wants an upbeat tone.
</P>
<P>
   The party also wants to look inclusive, and by no accident made
Kolbe one of the few members of Congress who got to speak. He stuck
to trade, a signature issue for him.
</P>
<P>
   Several conservative delegates took off their cowboy hats and
bowed their heads in a silent prayer in the only visible sign of
protest. Instead, a Louisiana delegate buried his nose in a
tabloid, and the crowd offered the same inattention given to
others, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
