<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Aug. 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former President Ford Hospitalized
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Former President Gerald Ford was taken to a Philadelphia
hospital Tuesday night, reportedly suffering from bronchitis, after being
honored at the Republican National Convention, officials said. Officials at
Hahnemann University Hospital were preparing a statement. Ford, 87, was among
three former presidents honored during the second night of the convention. John
Van Fossen, a legislative aide for U.S. Rep. Pete Hoekstra, said the Michigan
delegation was told that Ford was suffering from bronchitis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
67 Killed in Kashmir Attacks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PAHALGAM, India (AP) -- Four massacres by suspected Islamic guerrillas
opposed to a cease-fire have killed 67 people within a few hours in the disputed
territory of Kashmir, police said Wednesday. The separate attacks came as the
Indian federal government prepared to talk to the main guerrilla group in
Kashmir, which has been wracked by an Islamic insurgency for 11 years. Gunmen
killed 11 people in the Hindu-dominated village of Pogal in southern Kashmir
Wednesday morning, said Police Inspector-General S.P. Vaid of the Jammu
district.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Smartly Salutes Bush at GOP Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- John McCain smartly saluted George W. Bush at the
Republican National Convention on Tuesday, beckoning independents and Democrats
to support the Texas governor as a man of ''courage and character.'' Standing on
the podium where Bush will accept the GOP presidential nomination on Thursday
night, McCain deferred to his victorious rival. For the second straight night,
Bush addressed the delegates from the campaign trail
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
WHO To Release Tobacco Ind. Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Health Organization is accusing the tobacco
industry of secretly trying to undermine its campaign to reduce smoking around
the world, according to The Washington Post. A WHO report to be released
Wednesday details a sophisticated effort to pit other U.N.-affiliated agencies
against WHO initiatives, as well as using statements from scientists who have
financial ties to the tobacco industry, the Post reported on its Web site
Tuesday night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kansans Electing Board of Education
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- Candidates for the Kansas Board of Education who support
new science standards that de-emphasize evolution trailed in early returns in
two races Tuesday and led in a third. Three conservatives who voted for the new
standards were being challenged in Republican primaries by moderates who opposed
the decision; a conservative and a moderate also squared off in a GOP primary
for an open seat on the board. Linda Holloway, who supported the new standards
as board chairwoman last year, trailed Sue Gamble 63 percent to 37 percent, with
4 percent of the votes reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Inaugurates New President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's new president was inaugurated Tuesday and pledged
to maintain peace at home while Israel's government pursues peace with its
neighbors. ''I believe you chose me to bring peace among us,'' Moshe Katsav told
legislators, adding that making peace with the Arabs was best left to parliament
and the Cabinet. That was a veiled reference to former Prime Minister and Nobel
peace laureate Shimon Peres, whom Katsav defeated Monday in a poll of the
Knesset's 120 legislators.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Details of E-Mail Spy System Sought
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A privacy group asked a federal judge Tuesday to order the
release of details concerning the government's ''Carnivore'' e-mail surveillance
system. The Washington-based Electronic Privacy Information Center accused the
FBI of not moving fast enough to act on the group's Freedom of Information Act
request for the information. EPIC asked on July 12 that the information,
including the inner workings of Carnivore, be fast-tracked through a portion of
FOIA that allows for ''expedited processing,'' a 10-day time limit for
responding to requests. The Justice Department has not responded, EPIC said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Open Mixed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks opened mixed Wednesday after a similar performance
in New York. The Nikkei rose 10.64 points to 16,110.31 in early trading. In New
York, the Dow ended up 84.97 at 10,606.95. The Nasdaq was down 81.47 at
3,685.52.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giants 13, Brewers 8
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Bobby Estalella's bases-loaded walk in the eighth inning
scored the go-ahead run as the San Francisco Giants stayed in first place with a
13-8 victory over the Milwaukee Brewers on Tuesday night. Estalella drew a
five-pitch walk from Ray King that scored J.T. Snow, who had four hits and
doubled to start the Giants' five-run eighth. The rally was extended by two
Milwaukee errors which led to three unearned runs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
