<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Appeals to Yugo Opposition  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite an appeal by Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, opponents of President Slobodan Milosevic
in Serbia and Montenegro are showing little sign that they will
challenge the Yugoslav strongman in September's national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Albright appealed to the opposition Tuesday not to go through
with their threatened boycott of the vote. She urged the democratic
opposition in Serbia and the pro-Western administration in sister
state Montenegro to unite behind a single candidate to oppose
Milosevic in the Sept. 24 election.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin and Serbian opposition groups meet Wednesday in
Montenegro's capital of Podgorica. But Miodrag Vukovic, a senior
adviser to Montenegro's president, said the talks were a ''pure
formality'' and would have ''no influence on our previously
publicly stated positions'' to boycott the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not respect anything that derives from illegal and
unconstitutional acts,'' Vukovic told the private Montenegrin news
agency Montena-Fax. He said Montenegro would act ''as if there are
no elections at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the largest Serbian opposition party, the
Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk Draskovic, would take part in the
Podgorica meeting. On Tuesday, Draskovic's party repeated its
opposition to taking part in an election which critics claim will
not be free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Serbian Renewal Movement, the opposition front
stands little chance at the ballot box. Under Yugoslav law, winners
need on a plurality of votes cast without regard for the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ''With such a regime, there should be no discussion about the
elections,'' said Ivan Kovacevic, Serbian Renewal Movement
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The party's leaders are to meet Sunday to determine their
strategy for the Sept. 24 elections, which includes balloting for
parliamentary and municipal posts, as well as for the president.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the opposition to unite and rally behind a single
candidate has frustrated the Clinton administration, which had
hoped that Yugoslavia's defeat in last year's 78-day air war would
signal the end of the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   However, Milosevic has consistently outmaneuvered his domestic
opponents. He recently pushed through constitutional changes
enabling him to run again and reducing Montenegro's influence in
the union of two republics that make up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, Albright met with Montenegrin President Milo
Djukanovic, whose administration has received considerable U.S. and
Western European economic and political support. She said the
elections offer an opportunity to challenge Milosevic and his
opponents ''need to unite on a single candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These elections clearly are important and will provide some
kind of a meaningful test,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic declined to say if he had changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I can say at this moment is that we will not put up with
the constitutional violence that Milosevic is trying to use against
Montenegro,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
