<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bullock, Bush Had Deep Friendship  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Shortly before he was elected governor,
George W. Bush paid a courtesy call on Texas' most powerful -- and
ornery -- politician, Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   As they sat around the kitchen table for three or four hours,
swapping stories and ideas, the untested candidate and the 40-year
political veteran began forging a remarkable, bipartisan
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bond so strong that, after Bullock's death, his widow
feels compelled to step into her husband's place and carry his
message about Bush to the Republican National Convention on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If my husband was still alive, I feel quite certain he would
be here addressing this crowd,'' Mrs. Bullock said on her way into
the hall to watch Tuesday night's speeches. ''I've sort of felt him
in the last couple of weeks, guiding me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock died just over a year ago, at age 69, after battling
lung and heart disease for years. He had left the lieutenant
governor's job in January 1999 after eight years in office. At his
funeral, Bush remembered him as a man who ''embodied the Texas of
our myths and of our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   And a few weeks ago, Bush asked Mrs. Bullock to speak in a place
of honor, a little over an hour before he accepts the GOP
presidential nomination. Her appearance will help Bush showcase his
theme of being above partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bullock, who owns an Austin dress shop, has served on state
boards and traveled with Texas first lady Laura Bush. Her speaking
experience is limited to local groups. She plans to tell the
national TV audience about a friendship that ''surprised a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband was very picky, and a perfectionist. He wasn't
impressed by anybody or anything,'' she said. ''He could always see
through people -- he called them counterfeits -- five miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   But he felt Bush was genuine, ''his heart in the right place.''
And he would note admiringly that the governor ''worked like a
dog,'' Mrs. Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's trust and cooperation were crucial to Bush. In Texas,
the lieutenant governor commands the Senate and wields great power
to block bills pushed by the constitutionally weak governor.
</P>
<P>
   The two worked closely on education, limiting lawsuits, the
juvenile justice system and other issues they held in common.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bob was so fond of him, he really loved him,'' said Mrs.
Bullock, 51, who considers herself a political independent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bullock endorsed Bush's re-election over fellow
Democrat Garry Mauro -- even though Bullock was godfather to one of
Mauro's daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was pretty shocking. ... He definitely did get some
flack,'' Mrs. Bullock said. ''But I think Texans knew that Bob had
always been extremely independent and had done pretty much what he
wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bullock was one of the first to publicly mention Bush's name
for the nation's highest office, saying in 1998: ''I would be proud
to call him president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 0227 </TRAILER>
