<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 10:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 27 As Nasdaq Slips 17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Wednesday as benign economic
indicators were offset by concerns for second-quarter earnings,
leaving investors with no clear direction.
</P>
<P>
   In early trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 27.20
at 10,634.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 17.24 to 3,668.28. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 0.27 at 1,438.37.
</P>
<P>
   There was little news on which to trade Wednesday. Consequently
investors resorted to Tuesday's pattern, in which blue-chip stocks
moved higher on encouraging economic news and the technology heavy
Nasdaq stock market fell on concerns that earnings will slump in
the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three reports indicated that the economy is slowing
down and that the Federal Reserve Board's strategy of raising
interest rates may be working. If so, the Fed may leave rates
stable at their next meeting Aug. 22, which would benefit the
interest rate sensitive Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   In the first report, the National Association of Purchasing
Management said activity in the nation's industrial sector was
unchanged in July. Analysts had expected a small increase.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported construction
spending fell 1.7 percent in June. Again, analysts had forecast a
small increase in that figure.
</P>
<P>
   A third report found stronger-than-expected consumer spending
during June, and that the gain outstripped American workers' income
gains. But investors looked past that sign of economic strength
because the Commerce Department report also found that the prices
Americans pay for goods overall were unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1001 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
