<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Agrees to Vacation Photo-Op  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair has agreed to line up
his family for photos when they start their vacation in Tuscany on
Saturday, backing down from a ''no cameras'' policy declared after
a fuss over his baby son's baptism.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's office said Wednesday that the time and the place for
the photo had not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently annoyed that newspapers had published pictures of
Blair and baby son Leo despite the prime minister's appeal for
photographers to stay away from last weekend's baptism, Blair's
office said the family would not pose for photographs in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and his wife Cherie relented after Lord Wakeham, chairman
of the Press Complaints Commission, suggested it might be best for
both sides to agree on a single photo opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Wakeham said he hoped that after the photo session, ''the family
will be able to complete its holiday in private.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's chief spokesman, Alastair Campbell, said the prime
minister and his wife accept that there is a public interest in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a difficult area, in that the prime minister and Mrs.
Blair wish their children to enjoy as normal an upbringing as
possible and to be able to grow up without the constant glare of
the media spotlight,'' Campbell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1134 </TRAILER>
