<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Engineered Countless Crises  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- David Levy, serving under five Israeli prime
ministers in 23 years, has set off countless coalition crises with
thundering threats to resign.
</P>
<P>
   In what has long been a staple of Israeli politics, Levy would
withdraw to his working class hometown of Beit Shean in a huff,
refuse to answer the phone and wait for the prime minister to beg
him to rejoin the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Levy went as far as actually submitting a letter of resignation
only three times, once in the 1980s, once in 1998 and again on
Wednesday, when he quit as Prime Minister Ehud Barak's foreign
minister. The resignation takes effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Triggers for crises ranged from perceived ethnic slurs,
complaints about being shut out of decision-making to differences
over domestic and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Morocco, Levy immigrated to Israel as a teen-ager. He
parlayed a job in the building trades in Bet Shean into a career in
politics, representing Israelis of Middle East origin, who suffered
from discrimination at the hands of the European-dominated
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Useful as a symbol of national unity, Levy climbed quickly
through the ranks of the Herut party, now part of the opposition
Likud. He first entered the parliament in 1969, and since 1977
served in successive Likud governments as housing minister, deputy
prime minister and foreign minister, handing in a letter of
resignation to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir over an ethnic slight,
but retracting it at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Insults, perceived or real, led Levy to eloquent denunciations
of prime ministers and threats of resignation. Levy's exaggerated,
flowery style of speech and his carefully coifed crown of white
hair made him an easy target for comedians.
</P>
<P>
   After denouncing Netanyahu and quitting his Cabinet in 1998,
Levy accepted an offer to join Barak, who won the May 1999 by a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Though Levy came from the other side of the political fence, he
gamely defended Barak's efforts to make peace with the Palestinians
through concessions, but drew the line when it came to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the views of his old comrades in Likud, Levy said
Wednesday that Barak's offer to let Palestinians control parts of
Jerusalem was unacceptable. He said he could not be expected to
''try to explain policies I do not agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   If Levy, now 63, does not withdraw his resignation at the last
moment, his political future will be cloudy. He might return to
Likud, but some say he no longer has electoral appeal, and might
not be assured a place in the next parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1148 </TRAILER>
