<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maureen O'Hara Remembered  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- She came from Ireland, a
flame-haired colleen with extraordinary beauty and fire in her
hazel eyes. Maureen O'Hara became the Queen of Technicolor and John
Wayne's favorite leading lady.
</P>
<P>
   Her stardom was guaranteed from her first American film, ''The
Hunchback of Notre Dame'' (1939), in which she played Esmeralda to
the Quasimodo of her mentor Charles Laughton. When the studios
adopted the Technicolor process, she appeared in one spectacle
after another, often in pirate adventures including ''The Black
Swan'' (opposite Tyrone Power), ''The Spanish Main'' (Paul Henreid)
and ''Sinbad the Sailor'' (Douglas Fairbanks Jr.).
</P>
<P>
   Director John Ford chose her to appear in several of his films,
often opposite Wayne. The most memorable: ''The Quiet Man,'' in
which she and the Duke matched blow for blow in a classic
donnybrook.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara, who has made her home in the Virgin Islands since 1968,
was in California recently for a CBS telefilm, her third for the
network in the past few years. The first was based on the best
seller ''The Christmas Box,'' which has become a perennial show for
CBS. A road movie, ''Cab to Canada,'' followed, and now ''The Last
Dance,'' which will appear in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been No. 1 in our time period for all the shows,'' she
says proudly, ''and I hope we can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   She had been doing bits and pieces for the camera one spring
morning on Santa Monica beach. The ocean horizon was invisible, the
sky and the Pacific Ocean the same dull shade of gray. The film
company's array of trucks and trailers had encamped in the huge
parking lot next to the Santa Monica pier. The star's trailer
matched all the others, nothing fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like the urgency of television, but I don't like the long,
long hours,'' she admits. ''In the studios we quit at 6 o'clock. I
used to keep an alarm clock on top of the camera. When it went
brrrrr! I said, 'Good night, boys, see you all tomorrow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her long film career, O'Hara came across on screen as
a beauty with warmth and intelligence, a self-sufficient woman.
</P>
<P>
   At 79, her beauty remains unblemished. She doesn't dwell on the
rough spots in her life: two failed marriages, the unexpected death
of her greatest love. The only time during the interview when she
came close to weeping happened when she contemplated that tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Maureen FitzSimons (pronounced Fitz-SIME-ons) near
Dublin on Aug. 17, 1920, one of six children. Her earliest
ambition: to be the No. 1 actress in the world -- ''and when the
whole world bowed at my feet, I would retire in glory and never do
anything again.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was a noted operatic soprano, and her father owned
most of the top soccer teams in Ireland. He took young Maureen to
the games and to boxing matches, which she adored.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their mother's singing, the FitzSimons children were
raised in the theater. At 14, Maureen was accepted for training at
the legendary Abbey Theater, where she won all the competitions.
When American entertainer Harry Richman was singing in Dublin, he
met the FitzSimons parents and Maureen. In London, Richman spread
the news about the teen beauty.
</P>
<P>
   A film company asked if the girl could come to London for a
screen test. At first the parents said no, but an Abbey actress
convinced them it was the chance of a lifetime. For the test, the
17-year-old was plastered with heavy makeup and dressed in a slinky
gown ''that made me look like Mata Hari.'' Laughton and his
producing partner Erich Pommer had been looking for an actress to
appear with Laughton in ''Jamaica Inn,'' to be directed by Alfred
Hitchcock. They considered the test awful, but both were fascinated
by the girl's hazel eyes. She was hired.
</P>
<P>
   With the war starting in Europe, filming in England shut down,
and Laughton and Pommer moved their operation to Hollywood. O'Hara
went along to star in ''The Hunchback of Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I came on the Queen Mary, and the first stop in America was
New York City,'' she recalled. ''My first impression was bald heads
and billboards. I had never seen so many of either.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first impression of Hollywood: too much sunshine and too
hot. I didn't like the sun because I burn. I loved seeing the
oranges growing on the trees. The studio took us to a place where
there were orange trees and snow on the mountains behind. That was
the big photograph then. Now with the smog you can't see the snow
on the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 1941 Oscar-winning ''How Green Was My Valley,'' her
first film with Ford, O'Hara became a much in-demand star. For the
next 25 years she demonstrated her versatility in tear-jerkers,
Westerns, pirate movies, comedies and dramas, often before the
Technicolor camera, which seemed to have a love affair with her
lovely face and vivid coloring. Her biggest hits: ''Miracle on 34th
Street'' and ''The Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Rio Grande'' in 1950 marked the first of her five co-starring
roles with Wayne. She cherishes that relationship, and she proudly
talks about an interview he gave: ''He said he preferred to work
with men, and he had just men as friends. Except for one person:
Maureen O'Hara. 'She's a great guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   She also won over the predominantly male film crews, especially
the stuntmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 'McLintock!' I had to fall off a ladder three stories tall,
backwards into a water trough,'' she recalls. ''During the day, the
stuntmen would come to me and give me hints on how to hold the
ladder, how to plan the fall. They were wonderful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara's first marriage, to director George Hanley Brown, was
annulled; her second, to director Will Price, ended in divorce but
produced a daughter, Bronwyn, named after a character in ''How
Green Was My Valley.'' In 1968 she fell in love with Brig. Gen.
Charles Blair, as much of an adventurer as any of her swashbuckling
co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had been an Air Force pilot who had set many records,
including the first man to fly solo over the North Pole. He had
been a senior pilot for Pan American Airlines and had founded his
own airline, Antilles Air, in the Caribbean. He and O'Hara had been
friends since he flew her on the first flight to Ireland after the
war.
</P>
<P>
   The actress gave up her career after their marriage and made
their home in St. Croix, Virgin Islands. ''It was time I married a
wonderful man, and boy, I didn't want to waste a minute,'' she
says. ''It was the best thing that ever happened to me in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair was killed in a crash off St. Thomas in 1978. O'Hara was
asked how she heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in Ireland, and I had just had cancer surgery, and ...''
</P>
<P>
   She hesitates and stops, holding back tears. When she regains
her composure, her only comment is: ''a dirty deal.''
</P>
<P>
   She had little time for sorrow after Blair was killed. She
assumed the presidency of Antilles Air with its 22 planes, 26
pilots, huge expenses and dealings with government agencies. She
finally sold the airline, as she and Blair had planned. In 1991,
she returned to films after an absence of 20 years to star with
John Candy and Anthony Quinn in ''Only the Lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   She has continued to live in a large house at St. Croix, which
has been rebuilt twice because of hurricanes. She plans to move
into a condominium since her many grandchildren (Blair had four
children in an earlier marriage) are grown and seldom visit. She
spends summers in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always busy; at least I can never be called a couch
potato,'' she says. ''I work a lot for the aviation museums and my
golf tournament in Ireland. It all takes time. But it's good, it
keeps you moving, keeps you busy. It's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over the studio years, O'Hara laments that all of
her leading men are gone now: ''Laughton ... Tyrone Power, John
Payne, Cornel Wilde, Henry Fonda, Jimmy Stewart, Brian Keith,
Walter Pidgeon, and, of course, the old Duke himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were wonderful to work with. Every one of them became
personal friends of mine. I was very proud that I made two, three
and up to six movies with them. And never at any time when they
heard it was me did they say, 'Oh, God, not that dame again!'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Facts about Maureen O'Hara's life and career:
</P>
<P>
   Born: Maureen FitzSimons, Aug. 17, 1920, at Millwall, near
Dublin, Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Early training: Abbey Theater, Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   First major film: ''Jamaica Inn,'' 1939.
</P>
<P>
   American debut: ''The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Notable films: ''How Green Was My Valley,'' 1941; ''The Black
Swan,'' 1942; ''Buffalo Bill,'' 1944; ''The Spanish Main,'' 1945;
''Sinbad the Sailor,'' 1947; ''Miracle on 34th Street,'' 1947;
''The Foxes of Harrow,'' 1947; ''Sitting Pretty,'' 1948; ''Father
Was a Fullback,'' 1949; ''Rio Grande,'' 1950; ''The Quiet Man,''
1952; ''Against All Flags,'' 1952; ''The Long Gray Line,'' 1955;
''The Wings of Eagles,'' 1957; ''Our Man in Havana,'' 1959; ''The
Parent Trap,'' 1961; ''Mr. Hobbs Takes a Vacation,'' 1962;
''Spencer's Mountain,'' 1963; ''McLintock!'' 1963; ''Big Jake,''
1971; ''Only the Lonely,'' 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Marriages: George Hanley Brown (1939-1941, annulled); Will
Price, (1941-1952, divorced), daughter Bronwyn; Charles Blair
(1968-1978, killed in plane crash).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Appeal of Invisibility  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Invisible Man has never looked so good.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a man pulling the ultimate disappearing act has
fascinated people since ancient times. Now the special effects of
''Hollow Man'' add a grisly realism to the concept, which has come
a long way from the bandages and goggles that enshroud Claude Rains
in the 1933 classic ''The Invisible Man,'' based on H.G. Wells'
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Invisibility's appeal has always been part personal fantasy,
part bogeyman terror. Matt Greenberg, who created the new Sci-Fi
Channel series ''The Invisible Man,'' said it's a universal
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Growing up, I had dreams about being invisible, but not for
the usual reasons about eavesdropping or peaking in at people,''
said Greenberg, whose show deals with an ex-burglar implanted with
a gland that makes him invisible. ''For me, it was about escape. I
was a shy child, so I'd imagine being invisible and going to school
and nobody would be able to see me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Bacon, who stars in ''Hollow Man,'' also dreamed as a boy
about what he might do if no one could see him.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was a kid, I used to fantasize about it all the time.
Girls' locker rooms, girls' showers. It's the best way to take a
peek,'' Bacon said. ''I've since had the luxury of seeing naked
girls, so I don't really fantasize about being invisible anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For many early civilizations, legions of supernatural forces
acted unseen on people's lives. In ''The Aeneid,'' Venus pulls the
shades from Aeneas' eyes so he can see invisible gods fighting on
behalf of the Greeks at Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Mythology and folklore are rife with devices that confer
invisibility, including Jack the Giant Killer's cloak, the helmet
of Perseus, the Arthurian legend of Luned's ring -- right up to
Harry Potter's Invisibility Cloak.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, Dante and Ben Jonson wrote about fern seed or the
quartz heliotrope and their supposed power to make people
invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Stewart's best buddy in ''Harvey'' was a 6-foot rabbit
invisible to everyone else. Abbott and Costello met the Invisible
Man in a 1951 comedy. Mia Farrow had invisible escapades in Woody
Allen's ''Alice.'' And ''Memoirs of an Invisible Man,'' starring
Chevy Chase, turned the concept into a comic spy caper.
</P>
<P>
   In ''Hollow Man,'' audiences see Bacon vanish from skin to
organs and blood vessels to bone, all while his character,
Sebastian Caine, writhes in agony on a lab table.
</P>
<P>
   After he's gone, his presence is marked with crafty, creepy
computer effects showing Caine as a wispy ghost in mist, a
crystalline figure in water, a predator splattered with blood.
</P>
<P>
   When he first signed on, Bacon thought he could practically
phone in his role, since Caine is invisible for most of the movie.
For realism in interactions with the other actors, though, director
Paul Verhoeven had Bacon on set the whole time, painted blue, green
or black so he could be blotted out later and a digitized invisible
Caine substituted by computer.
</P>
<P>
   In some scenes, Caine is visible as a skinless monster of organs
and sinew.
</P>
<P>
   ''The complexity of what we did here surpasses anything we did
in 'Starship Troopers,' where you're making things that don't exist
and trying to make them fully alive,'' Verhoeven said of his 1997
sci-fi war story that featured armies of giant bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''To digitally recreate a complete, muscular man went way beyond
the amount of detail even that's necessary to build something like
a digital dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of invisible man horror flicks is fear of what can't
be seen, said Ken Graffeo, a home-video marketing executive at
Universal, which is issuing the DVD debut of Rains' ''The Invisible
Man'' on Aug. 29. ''With a monster, you can see it. But the real
horror is when you can't see it, but you know it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   The ring of invisibility pops up repeatedly, from ancient
philosophy in Plato's ''Republic'' to modern fantasy in J.R.R.
Tolkien's ''Lord of the Rings.'' Plato used the idea of
invisibility to examine morality, saying anyone with such power
would be like a god and could not resist the temptation to do evil.
</P>
<P>
   It was that theme that attracted Verhoeven to ''Hollow Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ''How far would you go into evil if you knew you could get away
with it? If the restraints of society were not around you, what
would you do?'' Verhoeven said. ''To see how the shadow takes over
the whole personality, so ultimately, only evil is left. That
process of deterioration is what I thought was fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells' 1897 novel brought a sense of science to invisibility.
The book delved into such practical matters as how to climb stairs
when you cannot see your feet, and how an invisible man can eat and
remain unseen when the food inside him remains visible until it's
digested.
</P>
<P>
   But like ''Hollow Man,'' ''The Invisible Man'' novel and movie
also examined the megalomania that might accompany invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a sense of power that comes with invisibility,'' said
Bill Warren, a science-fiction expert whose books include ''Keep
Watching the Skies!: American Science Fiction Movies of the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like being a ghost without being dead. This sense
of phantom power. You can have an effect on the world with no one
knowing who's causing it. It's like billionaires you never hear
about but who can make things happen the world over. They're
invisible men, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   While Verhoeven subscribes to Plato's dark speculation that an
invisible man would lapse into wickedness, Bacon is more
optimistic, saying he has faith ''in the basic goodness of people.
I think if people could become invisible, they might have some fun
with it, test the boundaries. I don't think most people would
become Sebastian, and rape and kill.''
</P>
<P>
   What would an invisible Kevin Bacon do?
</P>
<P>
   ''I would skip all these interviews so I could avoid that
question,'' Bacon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Plight Pulls Keneally Back  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFABET, Eritrea (AP) -- A group of elderly men and women look up
from their makeshift shelters and wave to the man with an elfin
beard and a floppy blue sun hat. Thomas Keneally, prize-winning
author of ''Schindler's List,'' is an old friend who has returned
to help.
</P>
<P>
   He wanders through the dust and thorn bushes of Afabet camp
where 44,000 of the roughly 1 million Eritreans who were forced to
flee a border war have found temporary shelter. Trailed by a small
army of curious children, Keneally stops at cramped tents to chat
with the refugees who huddle inside.
</P>
<P>
   In one such tent, he sits on a scruffy mat and listens to men
too old to be in battle tell their tales of woe, while young
mothers breast feed their babies and shy children peep from
darkened corners. He leaves the tent shaking his head, his face
torn in a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, he hears war stories from a grandmother who brews thick
Eritrean coffee over a charcoal burner in a terra-cotta beaker.
</P>
<P>
   Keneally is on his fourth visit to Africa's newest nation, one
he first came to know in 1987 when it was in the throes of a
26-year rebellion against Ethiopia. Another war, this time over the
border that was never properly defined once Eritrea won
independence from Ethiopia in 1993, has brought him back.
</P>
<P>
   He returns to the region again in his latest novel, ''Bettany's
Book.'' Set partly in the world of an AIDS worker in southern Sudan
in the 1980s and '90s as well as in Australia of the 1840s, it is
to be released later this year by Doubleday in the United States
and Random House in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Africa and the Holocaust, Keneally has written about the
famine in 19th-century Ireland and British convicts deported to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Schindler's List'' was published in Britain in 1982 as
''Schindler's Ark,'' before Keneally ever visited Eritrea. The
book, considered by some to be more a work of journalistic
reporting than a fictional account, was awarded the Booker Prize, a
top literary honor in Britain. And it captured the souls of
movie-goers with Stephen Spielberg's Academy Award-winning movie in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Sydney, Australia, in 1935, Keneally completed his
schooling then began theological studies for the Catholic
priesthood. But he abandoned his pursuit in 1960 and turned to
teaching before publishing his first novel, ''The Place at
Whitton,'' in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   He has had a celebrated writing career, and has been
short-listed for the Booker Prize four times: ''The Chant of Jimmie
Blacksmith'' in 1972; ''Gossip From the Forest,'' in 1975; and
''Confederates'' in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Keneally's journey to the Afabet refugee camp began one evening
in mid-June as he watched television at his home in Australia. He
saw footage of the Eritrean towns of Teseney and Barentu, captured
and allegedly looted by Ethiopian forces who launched an offensive
deep into Eritrea on May 12 in an all-out bid to end the two-year
war.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wreckage ... this was too far into Eritrea. I was quite
angry,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, the 64-year-old Keneally was on a plane from
Sydney to Eritrea's leafy, temperate capital, Asmara, 68 miles
south of Afabet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more or less a friend I feel a duty towards,'' he says of
the small country in northeastern Africa that takes its name from
the ancient Greek Erythree, for the Red Sea that laps at its coast.
</P>
<P>
   A cessation of hostilities signed June 18 brought a halt to the
war that broke out in May 1998 and has cost the two impoverished
countries up to $1 billion in arms as well as the lives of tens of
thousands of their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Though ostensibly about the disputed 620-mile border, the
conflict has deep roots in the complexities of the Horn of Africa.
Each country accuses the other of starting the fight.
</P>
<P>
   With its proud people and beautiful, sleepy towns nestled
between dusty plains and rocky mountains, Eritrea has enthralled
many visitors, and Keneally is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The romance began in 1987 when he ventured deep into the harsh,
beautiful country with the rebels who had dug bunkers into
mountains, and he fell in love with the people and their struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might have been a little bit of the Stockholm syndrome -- we
were all stuck together, and the conditions were pretty harsh,''
Keneally says, trying to explain how the affair began.
</P>
<P>
   So under the spell was he after his first three-week trip that
Keneally wrote what he called ''the only book I have written with
such direct political purposes,'' in support of the independence
struggle of Eritrea, a country he said that ''refused to be the
typical African victim.''
</P>
<P>
   His initial plan, inspired by the efforts of rock star Bob
Geldof in launching Live Aid to raise funds for the millions of
starving Ethiopians (and Eritreans) in 1984, was to write about the
politics of famine.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea was pushed aside as he walked ''like a
five-year-old holding my uncle's hand'' through the lives of the
Eritrean freedom fighters in their underground existence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Towards Asmara,'' published in 1989, became a work about
ending the war with Ethiopia and creating international awareness
about the Eritrean struggle for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated through the eyes of an Australian journalist traveling
with the guerrilla fighters and who marvels at their commitment and
organization, the novel espouses the cause of Eritrean independence
and is punctuated by exclamation marks as if to tell the reader,
''Believe this, it's incredible!''
</P>
<P>
   Keneally's experiences led him to believe that Eritrea could
become a rational society -- a model for the rest of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   He still rhapsodizes over its social cohesion, independence of
spirit and dignity, and recalls the exhilaration he felt with the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a much larger, better-equipped enemy, the Eritreans, he
says, fought with a combination of cunning and a never-say-die
courage and passion for their cause, supported by civilians who
lived equally covert lives operating in hospitals, schools and
workshops hidden in caves and bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   To many, the struggle was a classic one that pitted David
against Goliath -- the oppressed, romantic, minority against the
tyrannical oppressor, first in the guise of Emperor Haile Selassie,
then against Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam, the Marxist dictator who
overthrew him in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The war ended in 1991 when Ethiopian rebels -- who had fought
alongside the Eritreans -- entered the capital, Addis Ababa, and
Mengistu fled. Following a referendum, Eritrea became independent
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But although relations with Ethiopia were good for the first few
years, they began to sour, and tensions soared in November 1997
when Eritrea introduced its own currency and abandoned the
Ethiopian birr.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Eritrean troops were the first to cross the
disputed border in May 1998, as far as Keneally is concerned,
Eritrea is again the victim, again the unlawfully attacked, again
ignored by the international community.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are kicking from our 20-meter line, and they are in our
half,'' he says, using a rugby metaphor to illustrate the
territorial advantage Ethiopia now holds.
</P>
<P>
   The Eritreans offered him citizenship in 1993, and he would have
accepted, were it not for Australian law that prohibits dual
nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess Eritrea's progress in the past seven years,
Keneally says there have been positive gains in education, health
care and infrastructure. But he regrets that the one-party state
has yet to embrace democracy.
</P>
<P>
   If they did, ''it would be one less stick for the world and
Ethiopia to beat Eritrea with,'' he says, insisting he is not an
apologist for the regime of former guerrilla leader-turned
President Isaias Afwerki but a novelist who has also written about
the persecution of Jews, the famine in 19th-century Ireland and
British convicts deported to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Novelists, he says, write about fraternity and love across
borders, race and culture and about characters who have everything
against them ''because the best stories are there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1203 </TRAILER>
