<HEADLINE> Portuguese Discover Artistic Wealth  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA GILBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAGA, Portugal (AP) -- Most Saturdays, hundreds of local people
gather at the hilltop church here for weddings and baptisms,
lingering afterward outside the 18th-century monument to take
family photos.
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop is staggeringly beautiful: leading downhill from
the Bom Jesus church's majestic twin-tower facade is a giant,
330-foot-long baroque staircase in granite, studded with remarkably
ornate fountains and striking statues.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has some of the richest examples of such baroque art in
the world, but its historical value and importance went largely
unnoticed -- even for many Portuguese -- until an American visitor
brought it to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chester Smith, a Harvard University graduate who became
an internationally renowned art historian, arrived in Lisbon in
1934 at the age of 22 and was enthralled by Portugal's artistic
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of all the nations of Western Europe, none has a more glorious
history or a richer artistic patrimony than tiny Portugal, a
country occupying less than one-fifth of the Iberian peninsula
along the Atlantic coast,'' Smith wrote in the introduction of his
1968 book, ''The Art of Portugal 1500-1800.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith devoted a large part of his working life to studying and
cataloging Portuguese art and architecture, especially from the
baroque period. This style, prevalent from 1550-1750, is
characterized by detailed ornamentation and curved rather than
straight lines.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the country's finest baroque buildings date from the
so-called golden age of Portuguese discoveries, when navigators set
sail to discover the New World. Though then a small country of only
about 2 million people -- compared with 9.9 million now -- Portugal
gained huge wealth from trade in spices with the East and gold and
sugar from plantations in Brazil, which was then a colony.
</P>
<P>
   That wealth paid for the many monuments which still stand.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the baroque buildings are in the north of Portugal. At
Tomar, about 70 miles north of Lisbon, the Church of Nossa Senhora
de Conceicao is unremarkable from the outside and attracts little
attention. But inside, the detail on the delicately carved
Corinthian columns is astounding.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in his usual sober tone, remarked that ''the serene and
graceful architecture of the interior is unsurpassed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Smith's studies also led him to Brazil, which was
granted independence in 1822. There, he traveled widely,
documenting Portuguese colonial architecture.
</P>
<P>
   When he died in 1975, Smith bequeathed some 12,000 photographs
of Portuguese and Brazilian art and architecture to the
Lisbon-based Gulbenkian Foundation, a charitable body that promotes
arts internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Those photos and excerpts from Smith's extensive handwritten
notes form the backbone of a recent exhibition in Lisbon
celebrating Smith's work. It was part of a series of events to mark
this year's 500th anniversary of Portugal's presence in Brazil. The
organizers now plan to take the exhibition, entitled ''Robert C.
Smith: the Investigation Into Art History,'' to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''Smith was the right man in the right place, with the right
background and with the right convictions,'' said Dalton Sala, a
Brazilian who was the exhibition commissioner. ''He opened the
minds and eyes of Portuguese and Brazilians to their art and its
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith at first was drawn to Portugal to study the work of
18th-century Italian architect Luigi Vanvitelli (1700-1773), who
designed a chapel at the Sao Roque church in Lisbon. The chapel,
commissioned by King John V of Portugal and now a pool of calm amid
the capital's grinding traffic jams, is viewed as the epitome of
classical baroque.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was staggered by the beauty of its decoration in lapis
lazuli, rare marble, gold and silver and decided to explore
Portugal more widely. The chapel ''suddenly opened a door for me to
Portugal,'' he later said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith went on to Brazil in 1946, traveling widely as he studied
examples of Portuguese colonial architecture from Rio de Janeiro to
Sao Paulo and then to Minas Gerais province and finally the
Brazilian northeast.
</P>
<P>
   He documented the architectural styles employed in Brazilian
forts built by Portuguese military engineers in the 17th and 18th
centuries, many of them located along the coast to protect shipping
and key ports.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Principe da Beira fort in the Amazon near the
Bolivian border is an example of the ''prefab'' system the
Portuguese used. The stone was cut in Portugal and numbered and
sent as ballast in the Portuguese sailing ships.
</P>
<P>
   Following detailed architectural plans, the buildings --
including churches, forts, municipal buildings and jails -- were
erected quickly and efficiently. Slabs for pavements were also used
in fast-growing Brazilian cities. The ships' empty holds were then
used to bring back gold and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most notable Portuguese stonemasons, woodcarvers and
engineers who went to Brazil were from the region of Braga, a city
180 miles north of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Oliveira, an art historian and curator of the Braga
public library, says the demand for these skilled men in Brazil
created unprecedented administrative procedures as the local
authorities struggled to keep the artisans at home against the
allure of highly paid work in Brazil -- a kind of ''brain drain.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The exodus of Portuguese artisans to Brazil was so great,
especially from northern Portugal, that the government issued what
were the first passports, obliging Portuguese citizens wishing to
leave the country to obtain a special travel document,'' Oliveira
said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, too, was a kind of builder: Oliveira credits Smith as
being ''the architect'' of Portuguese art history, bequeathing
knowledge and approaches on which others have expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ''He built the foundations, the main walls and much of the
decoration'' of the way of researching and writing about art
history in Portugal, Oliveira says.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was as if he had a computer in his brain, his memory was so
good. He was the first to delve into the Portuguese archives and to
top it all he had enough money to hire staff to do research for him
and to own a car -- few in Portugal had such tools in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition ''reflects the way Smith went about things,''
said Helmut Wohl, Professor of Art History Emeritus and Fellow of
the University Professors, Boston University. ''Smith was
passionate about what he did and had a great capacity for work.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohl said he and Smith became friends, though Smith was ''very
difficult to know. I don't think he ever said a personal thing to
me. You never exactly knew what was behind the facade.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, at the University of Pennsylvania, Smith
obtained outstanding honors for his work. He became a full
professor there in 1956, a position he held until his death. He
also was keeper of the Archive of Hispanic Culture at the Hispanic
Foundation at the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Wohl said Smith ''was the foremost authority on European and
American decorative arts'' during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Smith published 14 books and contributed many articles to
journals in the United States, France, Portugal, Brazil and
Argentina on a wide variety of topics related to
Portuguese-Brazilian, Spanish-American and U.S. art. He was fluent
in French, German, Italian, Spanish and Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of his landmark research, the Portuguese and
Brazilian governments awarded Smith four of their highest national
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Portuguese architect Nuno Teotonio Pereira says Smith
took advantage of his outsider's viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ''People from abroad have a greater capacity of observation than
those living in the country. They possess a greater distance, a
better capacity to observe -- especially people like Robert C. Smith
who had the knowledge and wisdom to be able to appreciate what a
country has to offer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv for Aug 3-6 and Thereafter
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
