<HEADLINE> Cindy Margolis Coming to Your TV  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRADE CHERFILS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The romp on the sands of trendy South
Beach attracted hundreds of celebrity hopefuls, strutting their
stuff for the TV cameras, hoping to catch somebody's (anybody's!)
attention.
</P>
<P>
   And why wouldn't they get noticed? They were partying into the
wee hours of the morning with Internet pin-up queen Cindy Margolis,
whose uncanny ability to attract attention has earned her the title
of world's ''Most Downloaded Woman'' from the Guinness Book of
World Records.
</P>
<P>
   Margolis was on South Beach recently, taping segments of her
weekly, late-night show, which is due to premiere in syndication
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Cindy Margolis Show'' is billed as a sexy, interactive,
late-night party, complete with games, celebrity guest appearances
and ''webkini'' contests -- bikini competition to be judged online
by TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no place like Miami to have a good time,'' Margolis
said from a blue-and-white tent adjacent to the art deco club/diner
set she retreated to during commercial breaks.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen costume changes into the show, Margolis hardly
looked like she broke a sweat (she did carry her own personal
portable fan). She made all the work that goes into having fun look
easy.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old California native started turning heads after
turning a college assignment to start her own business into a
successful greeting-card venture. The home-grown cards with her
pictures on them turned into posters, and the posters helped launch
her career in modeling.
</P>
<P>
   When she created a Web site in 1997 to promote her modeling
career, she attracted a base of loyal fans -- her cyberbuds. The
site, filled with her swimsuit pictorials and other promotional
information, averages more than 500,000 visitors each month.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives started noticing that wherever Margolis went,
her fans followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It took me a long time knocking on everyone's door, 'Hello, I
have these millions of cyberbuddies, maybe you'd want them to watch
your show,''' she said. Somebody apparently was listening.
</P>
<P>
   Margolis parlayed her business sense into television appearances
on ''The Howard Stern Show'' and magazine covers. She even hosted
her own segment on E! Entertainment. Margolis also spent a year on
the TV game show ''The New Price is Right'' starring Bob Barker.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, ''The Cindy Margolis Show'' was created with the idea
that if she could attract hundreds of thousands to the Internet,
maybe she could do the same on television.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, she attracted a crowd to be on TV with her.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly 20-somethings who flocked to the set ranged from
those hand-picked on the street to curious thrill-seekers. The only
requirement was to keep the energy level up and move nonstop to
spinmaster DJ Skribble's beats, especially when the cameras were
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Performer Zamien Aki suspected that his nipple rings had
something to do with why he was chosen to be part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just standing out there and minding my own business and
someone grabbed me,'' said Aki, 22. The Detroit native danced the
entire night without ever putting on a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Lee, 26, didn't need an audition since he had ''the
look.'' The chiseled model just called the show's producers and
ended up taking part in the night's male webkini contest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I decided to do it just for the notoriety,'' Lee said. ''I
asked if they were going to show my face.'' He smiled broadly for
the cameras when Margolis introduced him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good to have on your resume'' said Hattie Williams, 19, a
dancer on break from the Alvin Ailey dance school in New York City.
She and her partner had just won a dance contest.
</P>
<P>
   The show also featured a celebrity guest appearance by
television's favorite alien, ALF. The furry creature from the 1980s
TV series was invited by the show's executive producer, Burt
Dubrow.
</P>
<P>
   Dubrow, whose credits include ''Sally Jessy Raphael'' and
''Jerry Springer,'' looked around at the end of the night and
marveled at the show that took him almost two years to bring to
life.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially impressed with Margolis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew within 20 minutes it was her,'' Dubrow said. ''She's so
damn likable. She's sweet. She's bright. She's charming.''
</P>
<P>
   Accolades aside, Margolis said she aspires to eventually become
a name brand, ''like Martha Stewart.'' But she warned, ''I don't
cook or clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Margolis: http://www.cindymargolis.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   SEA SICK?: Well, this sure beats eating rats on a tropical isle!
An upcoming Fox series, ''Love Cruise,'' is looking for 18 single
men and women between the ages of 22 and 35 to embark on an
all-expenses-paid cruise to an exotic locale. For 10 days and --
wink, wink -- nights, participants will interact in a series of
revolving match-up dates and games in search of the perfect mate.
At the culmination of the voyage, the winning couple will share a
grand prize. All participants must be willing to open up their
lives to the show (!) and be taped 24 hours a day. For more
information, log on to www.bunim-murray.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
