<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug.
6-12:
<TEXT>
<P>
   75 years ago: Actress Greta Garbo arrived in the United States
from Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   50 years ago: Warner Bros. announced the termination of actress
Lauren Bacall's contract by mutual agreement.
</P>
<P>
   40 years ago: Filming was completed on ''Sunrise at
Campobello,'' based on the life of President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
The movie starred Ralph Bellamy, Greer Garson and Hume Cronyn.
</P>
<P>
   Decca Records in Britain destroyed 25,000 copies of Ray
Peterson's ''Tell Laura I Love Her.'' The company said the song was
''too tasteless and vulgar for the English sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Silver Beetles recruited drummer Pete Best. The band
later became the Beatles and Best was dropped in favor of Ringo
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: ''Catch Us If You Can'' by the Dave Clark Five hit
the No. 5 spot on the British singles chart.
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: ''Soul Train'' made its debut on a Chicago TV
station.
</P>
<P>
   And singer Bessie Smith finally received a marker for her grave
in Philadelphia, 33 years after her death. The marker was purchased
by singer Janis Joplin, who cited Smith as one of her greatest
influences.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Michael Jackson paid $47.5 million for the
copyrights to 251 Beatles songs. He outbid Paul McCartney and Yoko
Ono.
</P>
<P>
   And producer Lorne Michaels, who created NBC's ''Saturday Night
Live'' in 1975 and left five years later, agreed to return as
executive producer. Michaels helped launch the careers of original
cast members Dan Aykroyd, John Belushi, Chevy Chase and Gilda
Radner.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: In a city block outside Macy's department store in
New York City, 5,271 tap dancers performed a choreographed routine,
claiming to break a record set by 4,877 tap dancers in the same
place one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: Sylvester Stallone signed a record $60 million,
three-picture deal with Universal Pictures, said to be the largest
ever between a studio and an actor.
</P>
<P>
   And Jimmy Buffett led an early celebration of President
Clinton's 49th birthday at the White House. Buffett and his group,
in town for a concert, sang ''Margaritaville'' and other hits at a
party on the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: Gene Simmons stuck out his bright red tongue, in
trademark Kiss style, when the rock band received a star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And filmmaker Steven Spielberg received the Medal for
Distinguished Public Service, the military's highest civilian
honor, for ''Saving Private Ryan,'' a film that re-enacted the
Allies' invasion of Europe on D-Day, June 6, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''We made a complete spectacle out of ourselves and that's our
job.'' -- Gene Simmons, as the rock band Kiss received a star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1214 </TRAILER>
