<HEADLINE> Additions To UK's Pet Passports  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA MICHELSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Fifteen rabies-free islands -- including Australia,
Japan and Hawaii -- will be added to the ''pet passport'' program
that allows cats and dogs to enter Britain without being
quarantined for six months.
</P>
<P>
   The program was implemented in February, beginning with 22
rabies-free European countries. Each passport certifies the pet has
a microchip implant verifying its identity and that it has been
vaccinated against rabies and tested by a government-approved
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 islands, which will be added at the end of January, were
included as part of an ongoing expansion process, Agriculture
Minister Baroness Hayman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries will be considered for inclusion in the pet
passport program in the near future, including the continental
United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously have to do this step by step,'' the minister
said. ''In reforming quarantine, we shouldn't be reducing
protection against rabies.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the program's implementation, more than 5,000 pets have
bypassed the six-month quarantine.
</P>
<P>
   The other islands or island groups added to the program are New
Zealand, Singapore, Cyprus, Malta, the Falkland Islands, Vanuatu,
New Caledonia, St. Helena, Ascension Island, Barbados, Montserrat
and Bermuda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
