<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Pledges Peace Efforts  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A defiant Prime Minister Ehud Barak pledged
Wednesday to press ahead with peace efforts, despite the latest
one-two punch to his political midsection -- the resignation of his
foreign minister and a decision by parliament to call early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Barak got a breather when the Knesset adjourned for a
three-month recess after giving preliminary approval to the early
elections bill. That gives Barak until late October to finish an
agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister can also use the interval to patch together a
new coalition and stop the unraveling of his government, which
began after most of his coalition partners quit last month over his
decision to go to Camp David for talks with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians said Barak must act quickly now. ''I think the
road toward a solution is open for both of us,'' said Palestinian
negotiator Nabil Shaath.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Mr. Barak decided ... to be tied down with his desires to
have a majority around him, or to start thinking of elections more
than the peace process, he will probably lose both,'' Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
   In quick developments Wednesday, David Levy announced his
resignation as foreign minister at a crowded news conference in
Barak's own office in the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said Barak broke the agreements under which his government
was established last year by offering the Palestinians control of
parts of Jerusalem. Levy said he could not ''try to explain things
that I do not agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy warned that now, an accord would require even deeper
concessions, and the people would not accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Then parliament passed a preliminary reading of a bill to call
early elections for both the prime minister and parliament,
achieving the 61 votes that constitute an absolute majority of the
120 members and that are required for future votes on the bill.
Only 51 members voted against and six abstained.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, disputing Levy, said no concessions have actually been
made because nothing was agreed at the two-week Camp David talks
outside Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   He told The Associated Press that he would continue his efforts,
but ''we are still quite far apart and we need certain flexibility
from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling calmly, Barak said he expected Levy's exit and regretted
it, but ''I am committed, first of all, to moving the state of
Israel forward and averting the danger of war, strengthening the
country through peace agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts discounted Barak's optimism and gave especially
long odds against his remaining in power. Asked what options Barak
has for reconstituting his government, political analyst Hanan
Kristal replied, ''None.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line opposition lawmakers said the countdown toward Barak's
downfall was well under way. ''One cannot have a majority around a
plan to divide Jerusalem,'' said opposition Likud leader Ariel
Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker Uri Savir, who took part in the Israel-Palestinian
contacts toward their first agreement in 1993, agreed that Barak's
government cannot survive past the end of the parliamentary recess.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Savir said, a peace agreement with the Palestinians
must be completed by then. ''I know the issues,'' he said. ''It's
doable and it's necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians failed to agree on a framework for
a peace treaty at the Camp David summit despite extensive personal
involvement by President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
