<HEADLINE> Speaker: Clinton Must Compromise  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert predicted
Wednesday the final stretch of the congressional session would be
''overshadowed by the elections,'' but urged President Clinton to
compromise in hopes of ringing up year-end accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would think the president really wants to get things done''
before leaving office, Hastert said in an Associated Press
interview at the hotel where he's staying for the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from routine spending bills, Congress will be considering
several key pieces of legislation this fall. They include GOP tax
cuts as well as measures that would provide prescription drug
coverage to Medicare recipients, make HMOs more responsive to
patients, and raise the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Hastert said, Clinton has not responded to his
overtures for compromise. When it comes to year-end budget issues,
he said, ''there's always a thousand excuses'' from the White House
for why they can't talk.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding presidential politics, Hastert likened Clinton's
recent criticism of GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush to
''trash talk in sports,'' and said Republicans won't rise to the
bait by responding during their upbeat convention week.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you react to a gibe then you're not laying our your own
agenda. You're responding to somebody else,'' said the Illinois
Republican. There will be plenty of time in the fall campaign to
respond to Democratic charges, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton provoked expressions of anger from Bush and his father,
the former president, with comments he made Friday: ''Nearest I can
tell, the message of the Bush campaign is just that, 'How bad can I
be? I've been governor of Texas. My daddy was president, I own a
baseball team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert cushioned his comments somewhat by saying he found
Clinton's remarks a ''little out of character.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe it's the remorse of not wanting to get out of politics
or whatever,'' he speculated, while adding, ''I think most
Americans think that's ill-mannered what they're doing anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert also took a poke at Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic presidential candidate. Gore, he said, has switched his
position over the years on abortion, guns and tobacco. ''You're
changing your whole philosophy of life. I think people look at that
askance.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are defending a narrow majority in this fall's
elections, and Hastert said he would campaign in as many as 40
districts in the coming month. At one point, he said he thought the
Missouri House district represented by Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt was ''in play,'' but then said he has no plans to go there
to help the GOP challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Congress returns from its summer break on Sept. 5, and Hastert
said he hoped the session could be wrapped up during the first week
of October.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do better when we're back home talking to our
constituents,'' he said, and polls consistently show GOP approval
ratings rise when Congress is not in session.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ''I've gone more than halfway'' toward Clinton to help
with several bills this year, singling out aid to Colombia, trade
bills affecting China, Africa and the Caribbean region and help for
economically distressed regions of the country. ''I had to push
hard to get it out of the House,'' he said of the final measure.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert also said he had called Clinton personally before
Congress completed work on its marriage penalty tax cut to discuss
possible changes designed to gain a presidential signature. Clinton
has vowed to veto the measure, which has been on his desk for
several days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish he'd sign the bill.... It's not tilted to the richest
people in the country,'' he said, rebutting a consistent Democratic
charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1418 </TRAILER>
