<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Debate Ban of Party  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL GEITNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germans need to ''get down from their spectator
stands'' and become involved in combatting neo-Nazi violence if it
is to be eradicated, a government spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Uwe-Karsten Heye, spokesman for Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, rejected calls from some quarters to go after neo-Nazi
''logistics'' by banning the extreme-right National Democratic
Party, saying such steps have been unsuccessful in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's always been new groupings again and again,'' he said.
''Bans clear away neither the subject nor the organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Debating a ban can be beneficial, but shouldn't distract from
the ''real task'' of organizing societal resistance to extreme
right-wing ideas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Success is possible only if people make it their business and
come down from their spectator stands,'' Heye said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was afraid that a ''right-wing mainstream'' was
forming in some parts of Germany that tolerates anti-foreigner
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of Germany's Jewish community, Paul Spiegel, echoed
the government's call in an interview in the weekly Die Zeit,
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A ''jolt must go through the population now,'' he said, to end
the ''message of agreement and mentality of looking away.''
</P>
<P>
   The main police union joined a proposal to seek a ban on the NPD
from Bavarian Interior Minister Guenther Beckstein, who argued that
the fringe party welcomes and even courts violence-prone skinheads
and serves as a cover for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   While a ban won't turn neo-Nazis into democrats overnight, ''one
can influence the structures,'' Beckstein said. ''These people, who
want to exercise the rule of the fist in the streets themselves,
really notice if the state goes after them with a tough hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Support also came from within Schroeder's Cabinet. Environment
Minister Juergen Trittin of the Greens party conceded that such a
step would be only temporarily effective. ''But that's not a reason
not to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Beckstein conceded such a step would be legally
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Banning a political party in Germany hinges on proving the party
is aggressively working to undermine the constitution. Such a
proposal must be reviewed by the Constitutional Court, a process
that could take years.
</P>
<P>
   The larger far-right parties, the German People's Union and the
Republikaner, hold seats in three state legislatures, while the
National Democratic Party is electorally insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to the other two, the National Democratic Party
has been gaining members -- from 4,300 in 1997 to 6,000 last year,
according to federal officials -- by staging dozens of rallies and
street marches. Much of their recruiting has been directed at
disillusioned youths in the depressed eastern states, which have
been struggling to overcome decades of communism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1434 </TRAILER>
