<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Prisoner Recovers Some Memory  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX BANDY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- Using patience and a children's fairy
tale, a psychiatrist says he stirred the memory of a man who spent
53 years in a Russian mental hospital and is now convinced the
patient is a Hungarian taken prisoner in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Since visiting the man, known as Andras Andreyevich Tamas, for
three days last week, Dr. Andras Veer has been trying to bring him
back to Hungary from a psychiatric hospital in Kotelnich, 600 miles
east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really need to expedite the paperwork required to get him
to Hungary where he can be treated properly,'' Veer, director of
Hungary's National Psychiatric and Neurological Institute, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian Embassy in Moscow and the Foreign Ministry in
Budapest have been trying to uncover enough about Tamas' early life
to issue him a Hungarian passport.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, little has been found in either Russian or
Hungarian archives to shed light on Tamas' origins.
</P>
<P>
   According to hospital documents, Tamas was transferred there on
Feb. 19, 1947, from a prisoner of war camp, suffering from
psychological problems, Veer said.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to speak Russian, Tamas could not communicate with
hospital staffers, who mistook his Hungarian for gibberish. Last
year, a Slovak doctor recognized some of the words as Hungarian and
an interpreter was summoned.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Hungarian Embassy in Moscow sent a consular
officer to visit Tamas. The Hungarian Foreign Ministry then sent
Veer to examine the man.
</P>
<P>
   Over a three-day period, Veer said Tamas' language skills -- and
some memories of his past -- began returning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am convinced the man is an ethnic Hungarian,'' Veer told The
Associated Press. ''I took with me a fairy tale book and he read
'Little Red Riding Hood' to me in fluent Hungarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamas said he was born in Turocszentmarton, a town in
present-day Slovakia now called Martin. It was part of Hungary
until the establishment of Czechoslovakia after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ''He uses a certain regional dialect characteristic of the north
country,'' Veer said, referring to the former Hungarian territory.
</P>
<P>
   But Tamas was unable to recall his mother's maiden name, or
whether he had any siblings. Officials at the records office in
Martin and the regional archives in neighboring Bystricka said they
have no record of anyone named Tamas.
</P>
<P>
   ''His name is quite foreign to the area and there are no records
of his birth here,'' said Jana Masnicova, an archivist in
Bystricka.
</P>
<P>
   Veer said it was possible Tamas moved to Hungary in his early
years and that local records were destroyed during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''He also spoke of going to Hungary and being in the Hungarian
army and fighting in the Don region during World War II,'' Veer
said, referring to the area around the Don River of southern
Russia. ''He described a 'hail of grenades' and being transported
by train to Siberia.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150,000 troops fought in the Second Hungarian Army under
Nazi command at the Don River in 1944. Red Army soldiers killed
about 90,000 Hungarians and thousands of others perished in
freezing temperatures trying to make it back to Hungary on foot.
</P>
<P>
   Tamas, who has dark hair and is nearly toothless, had to have a
leg amputated three years ago because of circulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Veer's goal is to get him to Hungary for treatment as quickly as
possible, where, surrounded by his mother tongue, the doctor
believes Tamas will recover his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Tamas remains trapped in time in the dingy hospital,
still believing he is in Siberia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1446 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
