<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Climb After Economic Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher Wednesday, rallying in
the wake of more encouraging news that left investors optimistic
the economy is indeed slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 100.00 at 10,706.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 6.16 at 1,444.26 but the
Nasdaq composite index gave back some earlier gains and was down a
modest 2.89 at 3,682.63.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stock prices surged after the Conference Board
reported that its leading economic indicators were unchanged in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Some technology companies surged after reporting
better-than-expected second-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Technology consulting company Sapient Corp. rose $18.938 to
$122.813 after reporting second-quarter earnings of 23 cents a
share, excluding one-time expenditures. The figure beat analyst
expectations by 3 cents. In addition, the company announced a
two-for-one stock split.
</P>
<P>
   And Protein Design Labs rose $20.656 to $153.25 after reporting
earnings of 23 cents a share, beating analysts' predictions of 18
cents.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell Computer was down $1.688 at $39.875 after an analyst
downgraded the stock to buy from strong buy on fears that the
computer retailer might miss its second-quarter revenue
projections.
</P>
<P>
   An important gauge of future economic activity, the Index of
Leading Economic Indicators held steady at 106 in June. If the
forecast is accurate, the numbers would mean a break from rapid
economic growth for the rest of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government reported that U.S. home sales
declined in June to their lowest level in two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors viewed both reports as signs that the Federal Reserve
Board's strategy of raising interest rates during the past year has
been successful
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three other reports also indicated that the economy
is easing after a decade of explosive growth. If so, the Fed may
leave rates stable at their next meeting Aug. 22, which would
benefit the interest rate sensitive Dow Jones industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rally came right after the numbers were released and the
feeling is that there's a relatively good chance that the Fed's not
going to do anything,'' said Tom Gallagher, head of U.S. equity
markets for CIBC World Markets in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Banking stocks benefited on the belief that lending and
underwriting activity of stocks and bonds will stay healthy if
interest rates remain stable. Lehman Brothers rose $5.313 to
$118.063, and Merrill Lynch rose $3.656 to $128.813.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues were ahead of decliners by a 5 to 4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 774.86 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.29 at 501.06.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1536 </TRAILER>
