<HEADLINE> PRI Under Fire in Mexican Politics  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- At any other time in Mexican
history, Sami David would be a shoo-in to be the next governor of
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite disasters, rebellions and persistent poverty, David's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, has never lost in
Chiapas. As recently as July 2 it won 11 of 12 congressional races
here.
</P>
<P>
   But that same night, Mexico's political world turned upside down
when the ruling PRI lost Mexico's presidency -- the head, heart and
soul of the party for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, as he races from Indian settlements in the highlands
to gatherings of ranchers on the coast, David finds himself
fighting a crucial battle for the future of his party in the Aug.
20 election, the first state vote since the PRI's presidential
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Even David, who is trailing in the polls, seems to be on the
defensive, admitting that past PRI governments have ignored the
poor in this state of 3.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The federal senator acknowledged at a recent meeting of the
state's agronomists' society that the PRI lost contact with its
grassroots communities, resorting to ''demagogy and simulation'' as
it practiced free-market economics on a national level while
promising social advances.
</P>
<P>
   But David warned that, as always, only the PRI holds the
solution: He said Chiapas needs to advance ''with firm steps, not
creating alternative projects that generate violence or social
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at a hotel in this state capital was the sort of
thing that has been a campaign staple for the PRI: The agronomists
are affiliated with a national farm confederation linked to the
party.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs the old system already is crumbling. With
the PRI losing national power, the agronomists' state chairman,
newly elected PRI Congressman Roberto Dominguez Castellanos, called
for political pluralism in the agronomists' organization, and
David's greeting was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not all of us agree with having invited the candidate of the
PRI,'' said Martin Mazon, a member of the organization's state
board who said he backs Pablo Salazar, David's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar, who claims he would be the first practicing Evangelical
to be elected governor, is a federal senator who quit the PRI in
May 1999 after demanding greater efforts to solve the 1994 revolt
of Zapatista rebels. He holds a strong and growing advantage in
recent polls, though nobody is sure how accurate those are in this
complex, conflictive state.
</P>
<P>
   He benefits from an eight-party alliance, including
President-elect Vicente Fox's conservative National Action Party
and the left-center Democratic Revolution Party, which was created
before the July 2 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas is Mexico's most southern and probably its poorest
state, one where the PRI regularly claimed 90 percent of the vote
until 1994, when a rebellion by Zapatista guerrillas shattered its
image of political unanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the state has repeatedly seen clashes between pro-
and anti-Zapatista forces, as well as what human rights groups say
are paramilitary bands backed by the government. The government
denies such support, and even the existence of the paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar and most human rights groups claim those paramilitaries
were encouraged by the PRI and by the federal government to combat
the Zapatistas, a policy they say led to the 1997 Acteal massacre
in which 45 Zapatista sympathizers were killed by PRI backers.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiapas vote is the first of three state elections the PRI
faces before it leaves the presidency in December. The party has
sent its top officials to the state, and Salazar claims it is also
importing electoral technicians to rig the vote.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign rally in the mountain center of San Cristobal de
las Casas, he urged supporters to vote early and stay at the polls
to ensure the ballots are not robbed or burned before they can be
counted.
</P>
<P>
   ''On July 2 the PRI entered the hospital for intensive
therapy,'' Salazar said before a crowd of 300 Tzotzil Indians. ''On
Aug. 20, we are going to disconnect the oxygen tank and give it a
Christian burial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
