<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ashes of Reuters Reporter Buried  </HEADLINE>
By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Friends gathered Wednesday
at Sarajevo's wartime cemetery to bury the ashes of Reuters
correspondent Kurt Schork, who was killed on assignment in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Schork's friends and former colleagues from the Bosnian capital
gathered at the graveside for the simple ceremony, held to the tune
of Dire Straits' ''Brothers in Arms.'' His sister Lisa Stone and
his girlfriend, Sabina Cosic -- a native of Sarajevo -- were among
those at the burial.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Schork's ashes were buried in Washington, his hometown,
and the rest were interred at Sarajevo's most famous wartime
cemetery, called Lion.
</P>
<P>
   Schork's ashes were buried next to Almira and Bosko, a Muslim
girl and a Serb young man who were shot at a Sarajevo front-line
while trying to escape the siege. They died in an embrace and
became known as Romeo and Juliet. Schork covered their story, which
had a deep effect on him.
</P>
<P>
   ''This city brought out the best of him as a journalist and as a
human being,'' said Schork's colleague, Sean Maguire. ''Kurt's
trips always brought him back to Sarajevo and this is where he will
now stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Schork, 53, and Miguel Gil Moreno de Mora, 32, a cameraman for
Associated Press Television News, were killed in a May 24 rebel
ambush in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Schork had spent more than 10 years reporting on conflicts
around the world, especially in the former Yugoslavia, Afghanistan
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora was buried May 27 in his hometown of Vimbodi,
in eastern Spain. In June, the Bosnian government awarded
posthumous Bosnian citizenship to both Gil Moreno de Mora and
Schork.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
