<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Invasion Shock NATO  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY ULBRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- All seemed well in the world on that
quiet day 10 years ago -- the Berlin wall had fallen, Moscow's
attitude was thawing and optimism was high. Then, in the middle of
the night, NATO ambassadors were roused from their sleep and called
into emergency session.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein's troops had invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was not directly involved, of course -- Kuwait was out of
its territory. But the atmosphere at that Aug. 2, 1990, session of
the alliance's top policymaking body was electric. Something
dramatic was happening. And it had caught everyone by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the first time since World War II that one country had
gobbled up another then declared that country didn't exist
anymore,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea, at the time a
speechwriter for Secretary-General Manfred Woerner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not just a Middle East crisis, but a real test of
principle, the sovereignty of states.''
</P>
<P>
   The invasion, which was over in a matter of hours, was a shock
to the NATO alliance. Intelligence had not predicted it. The
enormity of the situation, its impact on the rest of the Middle
East and its threat to a huge chunk of the world's oil reserves was
of deep concern to all the allies.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, five NATO members became direct participants -- the
United States, France, Britain, Canada and Italy. Others had a
peripheral role -- Norway provided shipping, Germany gave
anti-chemical warfare equipment and cash, along with nonmembers
like Japan and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   This meant, among other things, that some of the forces used to
provide the collective defense of the allied nations, which then
numbered 16, had to be diverted to the Middle East. That in turn
meant gaps had to be plugged back in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That early morning session of the NATO council was the first of
what became daily meetings to monitor the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   NATO became the forum for organizing the evacuation of foreign
nationals from Kuwait. It is also where the sanctions policy
against Iraq was coordinated. Fuel and transport for the Gulf
forces were arranged here.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important roles of the alliance, however, was
maintaining the united diplomatic front against Iraq, condemning
President Saddam Hussein and issuing statements about Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was grim. The mood of optimism that had been
growing with the end of the Cold War collapsed. It was also a
strategic shock because it wasn't predicted. Until then, the focus
of concern had been Iran. Iraq had been viewed as the bulwark
against Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   NATO found itself in a delicate position. Though it saw the
threat to Saudi Arabia and the Gulf states as a global crisis, it
couldn't enter the fray under the NATO flag. The Arab world was
extremely suspicious of NATO, experts say, and it is conceivable
Egypt or Syria might have declined to join the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Gulf War taught the alliance important
lessons that were to prove useful in later years in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The Persian Gulf War was the first time NATO had to engage in a
crisis outside its traditional zone and not connected to
territorial defense, even if that involvement was essentially
support and coordination. The Gulf conflict made it clear that
collective defense is one thing, but that the alliance must also be
diplomatically active and able to put together coalitions of the
willing.
</P>
<P>
   Those lessons were invaluable in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1603 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Racetrack importing feed as rain ruins hay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - An unseasonably rainy summer has
hurt the quality of local hay and is forcing Saratoga Race Course
to buy from western states and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has increased the price of hay for race track
officials to feed its thoroughbreds as well as for dairy farmers
who require hay with more protein.
</P>
<P>
   ''We buy hay from all over: Washington state, Idaho state,
Canada and whatever we can get out of New York,'' said Margaret
Pitney, owner of Thoro-Bred Feed and Supply in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of local farmers can't cut their hay - it's too wet,''
she said. ''It's gone up a little because of demand ... for decent
hay.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitney estimated the price increased $10 to $15 per ton.
</P>
<P>
   The price of hay harvested in New York has decreased from $102
per ton in May 1999 to $92 per ton this May, according to Muriel
Church, assistant director of communications for the Department of
Agriculture and Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Church said the lower quality of the hay was directly related to
the dropping price.
</P>
<P>
   The price of hay from outside New York, has risen because the
demand is higher, although there is not a set price.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pay about 12 cents a pound now for our hay, which would
normally be about 8 cents a pound now, but this year it's harder to
get,'' Rod Kosiczky of Triple Star Feed said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the price of high quality hay comes to $88 per
ton. At about 45 bales per ton, the increase comes to almost $4
more per bale.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McDowell, assistant manager of governmental affairs at the
state Farm Bureau, said the high-quality hay has special nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's rained on while cut, it loses nutrients, and it's only
useful for bedding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell said there are generally three hay cuttings per season.
Because the second two are all fresh hay, they are the most
nutritious. However, if the first cut is delayed or cannot be made
at all, only half of the harvest is fresh instead of the usual
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   The thoroughbreds are not the only ones in need of the nutrition
supplements. Dairy farmers have also been paying more to feed their
cows.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Titus, farm manager of Barbland Farms Incorporated in
Fabius, New York, said, ''It's been nasty. We've got about 300 tons
of hay that's been wet on the ground for so long it's rotting in
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Titus said that while some hay is still useable, the quality is
worse. They have already supplemented protein with soy, costlier
than hay, and the farm might have to look elsewhere for the hay
they need.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall quality is lower and the tonnage is lower,'' he
said. ''With the dry season out west, we may have to buy more hay
out there, which will drive prices up more.''
</P>
<P>
   Titus estimated the farm's profit will drop 3 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and trainers also say the flavor of the hay cut late is
different as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''As one farmer told me once, 'It's just tastier fresh,'''
McDowell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
