<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virus likely to spread, expert says  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) - The potentially deadly West Nile virus is
likely to spread throughout the state and even across New England
before the summer is over, a Connecticut scientist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''By no stretch of the imagination are we out of the woods,''
said Theodore Andreadis, chief entomologist for the Connecticut
Agricultural Experiment Station. ''It is quite possible we will see
a human case, if not in Connecticut, in New York, before the
summer's over.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday a West Nile authority from the national Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta told New Yorkers that the mosquito-borne
virus could spread into other areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people gathered under a tent Wednesday to hear
Andreadis speak about the virus during the station's annual open
house.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spend a lot of time outdoors, so I'm concerned,'' said
Paulette Leto of West Haven. ''I don't think we can overlook it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leto said she has confidence in the state's efforts to
fight the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know they're on top of it as much as they can be,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   No new cases of the virus were been found in the latest tests on
mosquitoes and birds in Connecticut released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was detected in mosquitoes collected from a Stamford
park on July 11. Tests on a crow found in a Stamford yard on July
23 - about a mile from where the mosquitoes were found - also
turned up positive for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Andreadis said Wednesday that knowing where the dead birds are
found is important. Four or five days before a crow dies it becomes
very ill and does not move much, making it a feast for mosquitoes
in that area.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent round of testing, 10,253 mosquitoes from 43
sites across the state tested negative.
</P>
<P>
   The virus first surfaced in the region last year, killing seven
people - all of whom were over 75 - and sickening 62 others in New
York. It killed hundreds of birds in Connecticut, New York and New
Jersey. Last month an infected bird was found in Massachusetts for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''As ominous are these statistics are, what is more scary is
that it has survived the winter,'' said Andreadis.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases have been reported this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who contract the disease experience flu-like
symptoms and never realize they have been exposed to the virus. New
York is the only area were muscle weakness is also a symptom, said
Andreadis.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is one possible cause of the potentially fatal disease
encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain. So far this year, 13
cases of encephalitis have been reported in Connecticut. No
evidence of West Nile infection has been found in 12 of those
cases; test results are pending on one case.
</P>
<P>
   Based on genetic analysis of the isolated cases in Connecticut,
the virus originated from the Middle East or Mediterranean area,
most likely Israel, Andreadis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still to this day don't know how it was introduced,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut this year doubled its efforts to trap mosquitoes,
setting up two different types of traps weekly at 73 sites around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state sprayed pesticide last week in sections of Stamford,
Darien and New Canaan after the infected mosquitoes were found.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station:
http://www.state.ct.us/caes/
</P>
<P>
   Centers for Disease Control: http://www.cdc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
