<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A weird summer in Toms River: No Little Leaguers headed for title  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - George Bell is painting his house this
week. That otherwise unremarkable fact is worth noting here, where
the powerhouse Toms River East Little League team that reached the
World Series in three out of the last five years was eliminated in
the first round of the playoffs this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a postal carrier who coached this year's team, said the
kids were under enormous pressure to repeat the successes of their
predecessors. The players said they did the best they could, but
for some in this Jersey shore bedroom community that has become
accustomed to nearly annual trips to Williamsport, Pa., for the
championship round, it was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parents were a little disappointed,'' said Bell. ''Without
a doubt, when you win and you have success like we've had for the
last five years, and it doesn't happen one year, right away they
blame the coach. I did everything I could, and so did the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have so much pressure at this age,'' he said. ''They're
only 12-year-old kids. Everybody wants to go to Williamsport, and I
was under a lot of pressure because I was the first coach after
Mike Gaynor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor won the hearts of Toms River and much of the nation by
leading his Little Leaguers to the World Series in 1995, 1998 (when
they beat Kashima, Japan for the world title), and last year, when
they lost the national championship to Phenix City, Ala. He stepped
down after last season to spend more time running his shoe stores
and coaching Pop Warner football.
</P>
<P>
   That left it to Bell and an entirely new roster of players to
try to match the successes of past Toms River East teams. But they
soon found that playing here can sometimes be like playing for New
York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, who expects nothing less
than a world championship every year.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't do it every year,'' said league official John
Karkovice as he trimmed the grass on one of Toms River East's seven
vacant diamonds Wednesday. ''Maybe it might be a little relief,
take the pressure off a little. But next year, I think it'll be the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Karkovice, whose kid brother, Ron, was the Chicago White Sox
catcher from 1986 to 1997, said people need to realize how
remarkable it was for a team to reach the championship in three out
of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The way Toms River East lost this year was surprising. Two weeks
ago, in the very first tournament game, the team suffered a
devastating setback. Up 10-1 in the fifth inning, Bell decided to
lift ace pitcher Tom Carlucci because he'd hurt his shoulder a few
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But a succession of relievers coughed up the lead, and an inning
later Toms River East had lost 11-10 to their crosstown rivals,
Toms River. A few games later, they were out, done, finished. No
trip to Williamsport. No rides atop a fire truck or parades down
Route 37. No visits to the White House or Rosie O'Donnell's TV
show. No highlights on ESPN, and no more baseball to play with more
than a month of summer left.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Carlucci broke down and wept in his coach's
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was crying like you wouldn't believe,'' Bell said. ''I
started to hug him and I said, 'Tom, you did everything you could,
but it's not a one-man team. You'll go on from here and do fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then he hugged me back and said, 'Thanks for being my coach.'
That's when you realize what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was disappointed,'' Carlucci said. ''I thought we had a
pretty good team. Certain things just didn't go our way. But now
that it's over with, it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Chuck Cerami-Nucci said it took him about a week to
get over his disappointment, throwing himself into daily Pop Warner
football practices and making an occasional trip to the beach or
the neighbors' pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we were the best team in the tournament, and we
didn't expect to lose any of those games,'' he said. ''But nothing
went our way. We all pictured ourselves playing on TV at
Williamsport. But it was tough to accomplish what the teams before
us did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugsy's, the local tavern where hundreds of fans gathered to
watch past Toms River East teams fight for the title, is a little
emptier this August. But owner Anthony Baiamonte said the community
is still proud of this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll still treat them like champions,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1628 </TRAILER>
