<DOCNO> APW20000802.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister, civic activist pleads innocent to prostitution charges  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Hartford minister and civic activist
pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges that he pimped women at a
Meriden massage parlor and assaulted a prostitute allegedly
pregnant with his baby.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Henry Price is charged with one count of first-degree
promoting prostitution, two counts of second-degree promoting
prostitution and one count of third-degree assault. Police say
prostitutes told them Price demanded sexual favors from them, got
them jobs at the massage parlor and took much of the money they
earned as prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   According to arrest warrant affidavits released Wednesday, the
48-year-old Price lured the women - in some cases, under the guise
of counseling them - into working at the Garden of Eden massage
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Price allegedly told one woman who resisted working for him that
''she was nothing but a 'ho' and she was never going to amount to
anything,'' according to one affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavits also allege that Price assaulted a pregnant,
29-year-old prostitute who would not have an abortion. The woman
told police that Price was the father and that when she informed
him he tried to ''beat the baby out of her.''
</P>
<P>
   First-degree promoting prostitution involves the use of force or
intimidation to get someone to engage in prostitution.
Second-degree promotion of prostitution involves managing or
supervising a prostitution business.
</P>
<P>
   Price left the courthouse Wednesday without comment. He is
scheduled to return to court Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Price supporter Prenzina Holloway said she feels ''from the
bottom of my heart'' that the charges are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a wonderful person in the community,'' Holloway said.
''He came too far to turn back.''
</P>
<P>
   Price is a well-known community activist and a vocal critic of
the Hartford Police Department. He was convicted in 1984 of fatally
shooting a drug dealer who sold him bad cocaine and sentenced to 40
years in prison; he was pardoned in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Price helped organize protests that followed the shooting of a
14-year-old mugging suspect, Aquan Salmon, by Hartford police
Officer Robert Allan in April 1999. Price has also led
demonstrations since the officer was cleared of wrongdoing by the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, defense lawyers and a lawyer for The Hartford
Courant argued whether the affidavits should be released.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Victor Carlucci said the documents
should remain sealed because the case is still under investigation,
and because witnesses in the case might be at risk for harm or
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Price's lawyer, Salvatore Bonanno, was neutral on releasing the
documents to the public but said he had not seen them himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm getting my facts from the Courant,'' he said. ''Prior to
today, I haven't been able to do any homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Elliot, the newspaper's lawyer, said everyone should have
access to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public has a right to know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Judge Robert E. Beach Jr. ruled there was no evidence
that releasing the affidavits would put anyone at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1648 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 81; Nasdaq Is Down 17  </HEADLINE>
