<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani talks briefly about cancer treatment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was uncharacteristically
open with Tom Brokaw during an interview at the Republican National
Convention, admitting to the NBC anchor he has undergone hormone
treatment for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made the disclosure Tuesday night while talking with
Brokaw in Philadelphia. It was the first time the mayor has said
what kind of treatment he is undergoing since being diagnosed with
prostate cancer in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of slipped - probably because a lot of people at the
convention asked me what I was doing,'' Giuliani said Wednesday.
''I told so many people, I thought I might as well tell Tom
Brokaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Daily News cited unidentified sources saying
Giuliani was receiving hormone therapy while trying to decide on a
final treatment. The newspaper said the mayor was being treated
with Lupron - a medication that blocks the production of
testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   While Lupron and other hormone blockers do not cure prostate
cancer, they can buy time for patients who want to evaluate
different therapies. The blockers are sometimes used before surgery
or radiation to shrink the prostate and reduce prostate specific
antigen, or PSA, levels.
</P>
<P>
   Lupron's most common side effects are hot flashes and impotence.
Injections of the drug, which are administered monthly or
quarterly, can hold the cancer at bay for years, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly refused to answer most questions about
his health since dropping out of the U.S. Senate race against first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on May 19. He has told reporters he
will inform the public of his decision on a cancer treatment only
when he feels comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not say anything further on Wednesday about his
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
