<HEADLINE> Study Looks At Ulcer Drug  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   High doses of a top-selling ulcer drug can reduce the
risk of
further bleeding after bleeding ulcers are treated, a study shows.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bleeding ulcers can be effectively treated with an endoscope -- a
long narrow tube inserted in the stomach to burn the ulcer. But 15
to 20 percent of patients have renewed bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that administering high doses of the ulcer
drug Prilosec after endoscopic treatment reduced the rate of repeat
bleeding. It also reduced the need for blood transfusions and
another endoscopic treatment and cut hospital stays.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers at Chinese University of Hong Kong studied 240
patients with bleeding ulcers who had endoscopic treatment in 1998
and 1999. The study, funded by the Hong Kong government, was
reported in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   After the treatment, half of the patients received high doses of
Prilosec intravenously for three days. The other half received a
placebo. For the next eight weeks, they all received the standard
pill dose of Prilosec, which suppresses stomach acid.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-dose group, 7 percent had another bout of bleeding
during the first month after treatment; 23 percent of the placebo
group had recurring bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Prilosec is the brand name for omeprazole, which is known
outside the United States as Losec.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Eric D. Libby of the New
England Medical Center said bleeding ulcers remain a common reason
for hospitalization despite advances in treatment over the last
three decades. He noted that Prilosec is not yet available for
intravenous use in the United States and the effectiveness of oral
Prilosec to prevent repeat bleeding hasn't been tested.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New England Journal of Medicine: http://www.nejm.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
