<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM to build new engine plant in Tonawanda  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TONAWANDA, N.Y. (AP) - General Motors Corp. will invest more
than $500 million to build a high-tech engine plant at its
Powertrain complex that will preserve jobs and better position the
Tonawanda facility to win future work, a GM official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new 711,000-square-foot engine plant will produce a
six-cylinder, all-aluminum inline engine for various GM cars and
light trucks, which GM did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking is expected at the end of the year with
production to begin in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   While not expected to create jobs, the investment will protect
the 4,000 employees at what is already the country's largest engine
plant. About 600 workers will be shifted to the new line, GM said.
</P>
<P>
   The state-of-the-art plant will be equipped with ''agile
manufacturing equipment,'' which provides the flexibility to
quickly make changes in the product line, GM spokesman Dan Greene
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's significant because it allows us to look good when
future business is on the block,'' he said. ''It's very good for
job retention and job security because we will be able to change
very quickly as market conditions demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tonawanda site was selected over several others, largely
because of the plant's productivity and incentive packages from the
state and Erie County, Greene said. GM also applauded a labor
agreement approved by United Auto Workers Local 774 members that
allows for more flexible work rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''A key factor is the management-union relationship,'' Greene
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and county Executive Joel Giambra announced
the deal at the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia,
where they learned the General Motors board of directors had
approved it Tuesday in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited announcement is believed to represent the
largest private-sector investment in the region since World War II
and was immediately offered as proof that the Buffalo area is still
capable of attracting big business.
</P>
<P>
   ''GM's decision sends a powerful message across the country that
western New York can compete for and win major economic development
investments because of the sweeping changes we have made to our
business climate,'' Pataki said. ''It is also a major vote of
confidence in the GM workers, who earned this victory with their
hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Attracting new engine lines is crucial for the plant since some
of the engines it produces now will be phased out in coming years.
The complex currently makes four, six and eight-cylinder engines.
Four years ago it was awarded production of a 2.2-liter engine,
known as the L850, used in Saturn cars.
</P>
<P>
   ''From our perspective it was almost life and death'' that GM
choose Tonawanda, said Ronald Coan, chairman of the Erie County
Industrial Development Agency. The agency approved a $22.5 million
package of sales and property tax abatements for the project in
May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Manufacturing is still the backbone of the Erie County economy
and Powertrain is the backbone of manufacturing in the county,''
Coan said.
</P>
<P>
   The state came up with a $13 million incentive package which
includes a $5.25 million commitment to upgrade roadways, $500,000
to improve access to the plant and $3.5 million to upgrade water
and wastewater facilities that serve the plant. The company is also
eligible to apply for up to $2 million in Empire State Development
Corp. employee training funds.
</P>
<P>
   ESD Chairman Charles Gargano said negotiations over many months
were difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a strong economy around the country and it makes it
very competitive with other states,'' he said. ''They do have 10
other plants around where they produce engines so we were competing
with them and it's always tough.'' GM has eight plants in the
United States, two in Mexico and one in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano added that although the state's expenditures are
earmarked for the plant, the infrastructure and water improvements
will benefit other businesses and residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
