<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousand mourn death of Bobov Grand Rabbi in Brooklyn  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Thousands of mourners gathered in Brooklyn on
Wednesday to say goodbye to Grand Rabbi Solomon Halberstam, who led
the Bobov sect out of Europe after World War II and oversaw its
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   The 92-year-old head of the Orthodox Hasidic sect died Wednesday
morning after being taken to the hospital with internal bleeding,
community leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   His death was not unexpected. He had been ill on and off for the
last six months, said follower Bemyamin Jolkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Tears flowed from young and old, men and women alike as
thousands packed a two-block area outside the sect's Borough Park
synagogue along 15th Avenue in a final farewell. Crowd estimates by
police and community leaders ranged from a conservative estimate of
10,000 to as many as 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The mourners included Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Rep. Rick
Lazio, the Republican candidate for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bearded men in black and women - their heads covered and wearing
long sleeved shirts and long skirts despite the humid weather -
cried openly after one speaker lost his composure and sobbed
through a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Loudspeakers were set up outside the synagogue, which seats
4,000, so the overflow crowd could hear the service. Several in the
crowd were overcome by the heat and were tended to by a private
Jewish ambulance service.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam was known throughout the community as a father figure
and someone who could be counted on for wise advice.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a sage of this community,'' said Chaim Greenfeld, who
described himself as a cantor and friend of the community. ''He was
looked up to by people who were not his followers.'' Some of the
mourners were said to include members of other Hasidic sects,
including the Satmars.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a father to everyone,'' said Ann Folger, a Bobov
follower from Flatbush. ''He put together all the families after
the war. He brought them up like his own children. He was a very,
very special man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bobov sect has its roots in the town of Bobova in what is
now southern Poland and was all but wiped out during the war.
Halberstam, a descendant of one of the first Hasidic leaders in
Europe, survived the purge of Jews by the Nazis, along with his
son, Naftali.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, the rest of the family perished, including the rebbe's
father, Ben Zion Halberstam, youngest brother and three
brothers-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he vowed to rebuild the sect. Eventually, in the
early 1960s, he moved with just a handful of followers from Europe
to New York. The group first settled on Manhattan's West Side and
later moved to the Borough Park section.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took the ashes of World War II and turned them into the
seeds of a new community,'' Jolkovsky said. ''He created a fertile
ground for a Jewish community. He was a father to all the orphans
after the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolkovsky said the thousands who showed up at the funeral came
out of respect for the man, not because he was a celebrity in the
community. In fact, Jolkovsky said, Halberstam shunned publicity
and was a very private man.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam, who remarried after the war, is survived by his son
from his first marriage, as well as his sister, his second wife,
another son and five daughters. His eldest son, 71-year-old
Naftali, has been chosen to succeed him as head of the Bobov sect
in Brooklyn. Halberstam was buried at Floral Park Cemetery in South
Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The Bobovs are among about 60 Hasidic sects still in existence.
The largest and most well-known are the Satmars, who originated in
Hungary, and the Lubavitchers, from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Community officials estimate there are about 10,000 Bobovers in
Brooklyn and thousands more in countries including Israel,
Australia and throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hasidism is not a denomination but a religious lifestyle and
ideology, which focuses on prayer and the study of Jewish holy
books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1724 </TRAILER>
