<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book Distributor Settles Case  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. and a former subsidiary
agreed Wednesday to pay $15.5 million to settle allegations they
overcharged schools, libraries and the government for books over
more than a decade beginning in the early 1980s, the Justice
Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit, originally brought by two private whistleblowers and
later taken over by the federal government and 18 states, alleged
that Grace and Baker &AMP; Taylor Inc., a national book distributor
that was a division of Grace until 1993, defrauded the United
States in direct book purchases and indirectly by overcharging
local schools and libraries that bought books with federal grant
money.
</P>
<P>
   Grace agreed to pay the federal government $3 million to resolve
the claims against it, the department said. In addition, Grace and
Baker &AMP; Taylor jointly agreed to pay $12.5 million to the 18 states
who joined the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   This brings the total recovery from the lawsuit to $18.5
million, because last year Baker &AMP; Taylor paid the federal
government $3 million to resolve its direct claims against that
Charlotte, N.C.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ''This settlement demonstrates the United States' commitment to
protecting federal funds from fraud and abuse,'' said acting
Assistant Attorney General David Ogden, head of the department's
civil division.
</P>
<P>
   In Charlotte, Jim Ulsamer, president of Baker &AMP; Taylor Retail,
said the settlement resolves all claims ''without admitting any
wrongdoing'' by his company. Continuing the litigation would only
have diverted senior managers from new business initiatives,
Ulsamer said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit under the federal False Claims Act sought damages
and penalties based on Baker &AMP; Taylor's contracts with
institutional customers, in which the company agreed to provide
discounts of about 40 percent on trade books, but then failed to
provide the full discounts by misclassifying trade titles into
non-trade categories. Meanwhile, Baker &AMP; Taylor was providing full
trade discounts on the same books to retailers, the government
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trade books are those intended for a general readership.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, California, Connecticut, Florida, Hawaii, Idaho,
Kentucky, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, Nevada, New Mexico,
North Carolina, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, Vermont and Wisconsin
joined the lawsuit claiming damages on behalf of their schools and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The two whistleblowers who brought the original lawsuit, Robert
Costa, head librarian for the city of Richmond, Va., and Ronald
Thornburg, a former Baker &AMP; Taylor sales representative, will share
a portion of the settlement payment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1731 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court agrees to have an outsider monitor death penalty for race bias </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Because no one method can determine whether
minorities are sentenced to die more than whites, the state Supreme
Court ruled Wednesday that a special judge will continue to review
the question of race and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The high court made the ruling as it upheld death sentences in
three cases where white victims were murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Included in that trio was the case of Ambrose Harris, who raped
and murdered artist Kristin Huggins in 1992, then drove the woman's
car around Trenton with the body stuffed in the trunk. While on
death row, Harris allegedly stomped fellow inmate Robert ''Mudman''
Simon to death.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty opponents, including the state Public Defender's
Office, argue that those who kill whites are sentenced to death
more often than those convicted of murdering minorities. Opponents
also contend minority defendants are more likely to face execution
than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least 1992, the Supreme Court has reviewed each death
sentence to determine if the penalty is appropriate. This review
follows any appeal of the trial or conviction. Wednesday's ruling
is the second in the court's two-part examination of its review
process.
</P>
<P>
   By a 6-1 vote, the justices agreed to keep in place presiding
state Appellate Division Judge David S. Baime, who will review that
process and update yearly the statistical analysis of death
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The judge is needed because the court found no single test or
method that best examines the impact of race.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process is far more complicated than counting the number
of defendants by race and the number of death penalties meted
out,'' Chief Justice Deborah Poritz wrote in the 31-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''A myriad of discretionary decisions are made at every level in
the system, and sorting out their relationship to the race of
either defendants or victims is complex and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a statistical model is ''largely untested and ... its
usefulness is uncertain,'' Poritz wrote. Whatever decision the
court makes, it must be reviewed in the future, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The importance of understanding whether racial discrimination
infects our system of capital punishment requires that we make this
effort,'' Poritz said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Harris, the court again affirmed death sentences for
Robert W. Morton and Richard Feaster. All three convictions and
sentences were upheld in earlier decisions. Wednesday's rulings
were the second phase of the automatic review for each death
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Morton stabbed attendant Michael Eck to death during the 1993
robbery of a gas station in Delran. Feaster's death sentence is for
the 1993 murder of a gas station employee in Deptford Township.
</P>
<P>
   These decisions are the final state appeals for each defendant.
Appeals to the federal courts are being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed because all three had their verdicts upheld
and we think they're glaring examples of this problem,'' said
Deputy Public Defender Claudia Van Wyk. ''When you look at the
whole system, it is the people who kill white people that receive
death sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Wyk said her office is pleased the court will continue to
review the effect of race in death sentences. Public defenders will
also ask for additional judicial review of cases when that special
judge updates his studies.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey joins five other states where the death sentence is
being studied, said Richard Dieter, executive director of the Death
Penalty Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   But to study race, reviewers need to look at all crimes where
the death penalty was a possibility, not just those where verdicts
are reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To New Jersey's credit, they're willing to do that kind of
review,'' Dieter said.
</P>
<P>
   For some death penalty opponents, this study is clearly needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why we're calling for a moratorium in New Jersey,''
said Lois Seeligsohn, a spokeswoman for New Jerseyans for a Death
Penalty Moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're calling for two years to study the system, which is
broken. Then figure out how we can do it better. I don't think we
can,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
