<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compassionate about Hillary's campaign? Fuggedaboutit!  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - Can Hillary Rodham Clinton and her Senate
campaign escape criticism among thousands of Republicans attending
their national convention this week? As they say in New York City,
fuggedaboutit!
</P>
<P>
   While party leaders try to keep the negativity low, many
delegates cannot be restrained.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know about you, but I don't want to be lectured for
the next six years by Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' U.S. Rep. Rick
Lazio, her opponent for the Senate seat, told cheering New York
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   During Lazio's abbreviated stay, party staffers passed out
stickers stating: ''Save NY. Stop Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George E. Pataki found an innovative way to praise
Laura Bush, wife of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will finally have a first lady we can be proud of,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the North Carolina and Delaware delegations, Pataki
identified himself as ''the one who retired Governor Cuomo, and,
yes, I am the governor of the state that is going to retire Hillary
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican convention officials have said repeatedly they want
the convention to be about the positive Republican message, so no
one has said much about the current first lady during the
convention's nightly sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But once outside, New Yorkers and other state delegates talk
about Clinton among themselves and to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain said he is encouraged that she is stuck
at 46 percent in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''If she was running against Howdy Doody, she'd be at 46
percent,'' he said. U.S. Rep. Asa Hutchison, R-Ark., chimed in:
''The only thing I'm afraid of is Hillary will come back to
Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just the public officials. ''I just think Hillary
Clinton is very aggressive and pushy,'' said Ruthie Johnson, 75, of
Hayden Lake, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Weber, a conservative activist from Sparks, Nev., said Mrs.
Clinton ''just rubs me the wrong way the minute she opens her
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She's not very first-ladyesque,'' said Ryan Erwin, executive
director of the Nevada GOP. ''She doesn't have the traditional,
older, dignified glamor. She's not somebody you'd truly like to sit
down with and enjoy some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent Clar, chairman of the Idaho Republican Party: ''I've just
always thought that Hillary Clinton came across as a little
arrogant, that she thought her ideas were always right.''
</P>
<P>
   An Albany T-shirt business called Votershop.com even got into
the act, selling anti-Clinton T-shirts at a hotel the New York GOP
made its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided we wanted to do some T-shirts, so people could get
their feelings off their chests and on their sleeves,'' said
37-year-old Mark Jones of Altamont, one of the business founders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular shirts says, ''I LOVE NY (It's Hillary I
can't stand).''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's positive,'' New York GOP Party spokesman Dan Allen
laughed. ''They're in a positive revenue situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
