<HEADLINE> 16 more birds confirmed to have West Nile Virus in NYC  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Sixteen more birds in New York City - 14 of them
on Staten Island - have been diagnosed with the West Nile Virus,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ground spraying had already been scheduled for the island
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two birds most recently found infected in Manhattan were in
Central Park and in Washington Heights at 155th Street, Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rockland County - which yielded the first infected fowl of the
season and still has the highest tally in the area - added 10 more
sick birds to its list of 48, the county executive's office said.
Most of the latest batch were in Clarkstown.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester, a blue jay found dead in Yonkers last month was
the 11th county bird to test positive for the virus, the county
Health Department said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year the virus has appeared only in birds and
mosquitoes - bloodsucking insects that can spread West Nile to
humans. City Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen said the city has
ruled out 160 cases of people who had come down with West Nile-like
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   While some people infected with West Nile show no symptoms,
others suffer from a flu-like condition that can include high
fever, gastrointenstinal problems, muscle ache, headache, or mental
confusion. West Nile can also cause encephalitis, a swelling of the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with Queens as the epicenter, the first U.S. case of
West Nile was reported in late August; a total of seven people in
the New York area died and 62 were infected.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is commonly found in Africa, Eastern Europe, West Asia
and the Middle East. Its appearance in the New York area last year
prompted a massive campaign of aerial and ground spraying to kill
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Central Park, Alley Pond Park in Queens, and the area of
Manhattan and the Bronx north of 110th Street and south of Dyckman
Street, were scheduled to be sprayed with insecticide Friday night.
Central Park and Alley Pond Park have been sprayed before, but
additional mosquitoes were found afterward, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of birds infected with West Nile have been found on
Staten Island, but Giuliani said no one knows yet why the borough
seems to be the hotbed for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commissioner (Cohen) the other day came to the conclusion
that a lot of the activity is located there - if you want to call
it the epicenter, that would be a fair conclusion,'' the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, a total of 32 West Nile-infected birds have been found
in all five boroughs - 27 in Staten Island, three in Queens and two
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani again said it would be helpful if New Jersey
communities would conduct precautionary spraying for mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
   ''We talk to them and we make recommendations, but it's their
decision,'' he said. ''It's a medical, scientific, and I guess,
ultimately a political decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Rockland and Westchester counties, no new spraying
was announced because the areas where the birds were found have
already been sprayed. Spraying was planned for Wednesday night in
Ardsley and parts of Ossining and White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   In Rockland County, spraying was scheduled for Wednesday night
in New Square and parts of Spring Valley, Kaser and New Hemstead.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nyc.gov/health
</P>
<P>
   http://www.westchestergov.com/health
</P>
<P>
   http://www.co.rockland.ny.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1757 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY faces crisis of soaring electricity prices  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The price of powering New York City is
skyrocketing, creating an electricity crisis that's turning up the
heat most on the city's poorest residents, state legislators said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the coolest July since 1914, average rates for Con
Edison's 3.3 million residential customers were 43 percent higher
during the month than last July.
</P>
<P>
   ''The energy policies of this state have failed, and failed
miserably,'' said Paul Tonko, chairman of the State Assembly Energy
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He joined six other members of the Assembly at a hearing that
discussed the question of whether electricity bills would continue
to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know,'' was Con Ed chairman Eugene McGrath's reply.
</P>
<P>
   Tonko said New Yorkers who suffer most are older people on fixed
incomes and low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver laid the blame on last August's
deregulation plan. Con Ed no longer produces its own power; it
transmits electricity bought from independently owned generating
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That, Silver said, allows ''one of the nation's biggest
utilities to pass higher wholesale prices on to consumers,''
instead of creating healthy competition that keeps prices in check.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Helmer, head of the state Public Service Commission that
regulates utilities, told the hearing that in the long run, the
state plan will create competition, which with more plants in the
works to meet demand, will result in ''a competitive marketplace
for electricity that would benefit consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial customers, including hospitals and manufacturers,
face an even higher average increase - 49 percent for July over
that month last year.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarket owner Alfredo Rodriguez, who appeared at the
hearing, called his own electricity bills ''a nail in the coffin''
- for the month, 130 percent over July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old businessman with a wife and three children owns
an Associated market in East Harlem. He laid out the bills on an
oak table outside the New York Bar Association hearing room where
the panel was grilling the utility executive: a Con Ed bill of
$5,477 for July 1999, versus $12,139 for July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm debating whether to pay the bill,'' said Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath told the legislators that this year's higher costs
reflect the prices his utility is paying to buy electricity at
unpredictable market rates. The generating companies, in turn, are
absorbing the rising prices of the oil that fuels many plants, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not the supplier. We're like FedEx, delivering a product
from a catalog,'' said McGrath, noting that FedEx, like his
utility, would not be held responsible for the price of an item.
</P>
<P>
   Tonko, the energy committee chairman, countered that states
surrounding New York achieve lower prices through energy policies
that are ''more aggressively consumer-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Con Ed is enjoying ''risk-free capitalism,'' with demand
in a booming economy outstripping energy supply and inflating
prices further.
</P>
<P>
   The typical Con Ed residential bill for July 1999 was about $51,
while the average bill hit $73 last month, reflecting an increase
from 17.3 to 24.5 cents per kilowatt hour. The cost per kilowatt
hour for large businesses jumped from 16.4 to 24.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath promised that his utility would work with state
regulators and suppliers to try to knock down costs. Meanwhile, he
suggested, unhappy customers can do business with other unregulated
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez insisted that ''if you switch, you get two bills -
and one is from Con Ed, for the line, which is a monopoly. They're
the only game in town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1802 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former security guard says he was defending himself in fatal assault </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A former Trump Plaza Hotel &AMP; Casino
guard accused in the fatal beating of an unruly gambler took the
stand in his own defense Wednesday, saying he resorted to force to
protect himself and other guards from the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petty, 35, said he shoved Hue To into a chair in the
casino's security office because To, who had been ejected from the
casino for harassing and panhandling other gamblers, had threatened
to kill Petty and three other guards and was swinging wildly.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was threatening to kill me,'' said Petty, under questioning
from Chief Assistant Atlantic County Prosecutor Ellen Loughney.
''Mr. To had his hands in my face and I pushed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was scared. I wanted to keep this man away from myself and
others,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   To, 25, of Plainfield, died of a spinal injury after Petty
allegedly threw him into a door and kicked him. Petty is charged
with aggravated manslaughter and four counts of witness tampering
in the Sept. 8, 1998, incident.
</P>
<P>
   The tampering charge stems from Petty's alleged attempts to
bully the other security guards who were present into lying for him
in their official reports on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Tuesday, Petty blamed fellow guard James Marsico
for roughing up To.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what Marsico did, but he spun him around and
pounded his face against the wall,'' Petty testified. Loughney then
accused Petty of blaming Marsico because Marsico was the first
guard to come forward to say the incident didn't happen the way the
guards first said it did.
</P>
<P>
   Marsico's credibility was impeached Wednesday when the defense
presented a witness who said Marsico admitted to him that he hadn't
seen the fatal altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Doran, an Atlantic City police detective who is a close
friend of Marsico's, said Marsico called to ask his advice on
whether Marsico could get in trouble if his official statement was
found to be inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, he said Petty was the one who threw To into a
door and kicked him ''like a football.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted to his friend that he didn't see what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he was in an adjoining room and that he heard noises
but that he didn't observe anything,'' Doran said.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are expected to begin Thursday. If convicted,
Petty faces 10 to 30 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
