<HEADLINE> Nassau medical center employee charges hospital chairman with sex harassment </HEADLINE>
By PAT MILTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) - A secretary at the Nassau County Medical
Center has charged the hospital board chairman with threatening to
dismiss her if she did not engage in sex acts with him, the woman's
attorney said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Pistorio McGrath, a 36-year-old mother of three, claims
she was subjected to numerous requests for sex by Eric Rosenblum,
the hospital chairman, since shortly after she began working for
Rosenblum as his administrative assistant in December.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath charges in a notice of claim, a preliminary step to a
lawsuit, served on Nassau County Tuesday that Rosenblum asked her
to engage in group sex, sent letters and e-mails seeking sex and on
one occasion grabbed her hand and forced it on his crotch.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was lewd and disgusting,'' said McGrath's attorney, Alan
Sanders. ''We are not talking about ''did he or didn't he cross
over the line here,'' he said. ''This man clearly sexually
assaulted this woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblum, an attorney, of Levittown, was appointed board
chairman by Nassau County Executive Thomas Gulotta. He called the
allegations lies and said he does not intend to resign his
position. The job is unsalaried.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County spokeswoman Diane Baumert-Moyik, said the county
attorney is reviewing the notice of claim which names Rosenblum and
Nassau County as respondents. The Nassau County Medical Center
board - which includes state and county appointees - is conducting
an internal investigation into the complaint, Baumert-Moyik said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will await any recommendations by the board,'' she said.
''Ultimately it is up to the county legislature to act on the
recommendations if there are any.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath also has filed a complaint with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, a preliminary step to filing a federal
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, of Jericho, said she did not come forward sooner
because she feared losing her $30,000-a-year job. She and her
husband, John, a construction worker, have six children.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was intimidated by this man,'' Sanders said, adding that
Rosenblum, a Republican party leader, told McGrath it would do her
no good to report him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told her point blank (he has) every judge in Nassau County
in his pocket,'' said Sanders. At her request, McGrath has been
transferred to another department at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he has copies of letters Rosenblum allegedly sent
McGrath and a disc filled with e-mails as evidence. In addition, he
said other female employees have contacted him with similar
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ''My client wants me to send a message to all employers who
think they are above the law that they will be held accountable for
their actions,'' Sanders said.
</P>
</TEXT>
