<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court says grandparents can't be forced to support grandchildren  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Grandparents can't be forced to provide
financial support for their grandchildren, even if they're born to
minor children, an appeals court ruled this week.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a teen mom sued the teen dad's father to help
support the South Jersey girl's 21-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was 14 when she became pregnant and the boy was 15.
Their daughter was born in November 1998. Court documents don't
identify the teens or their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The teen girl lives with her mother, who helps support the baby.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the argument that grandparents should be held
responsible because the teens don't have the resources to care for
the child themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that the state Legislature has passed laws to
hold a parent responsible for certain costs related to their
children's behavior, such as school vandalism, but has never said
they should be responsible for the offspring of their minor
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no statutory or judicial requirement that the parents
of minor girls who have children out of wedlock must support their
grandchildren. Nor is there a statutory or judicial requirement
that the parents of minor boys who father children out of wedlock
must support their grandchild,'' the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such an obligation could dramatically change the financial and
other relationship within a family, and in our view such a policy
change should come from the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Sutton, an attorney who represented the girl's mother,
said she ''was disappointed in the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The ruling leaves these infants with absolutely no legal
rights of support because their parents are minors under the law,''
Sutton said. ''They have no means of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton had argued that it is a parent's obligation to support
their minor child's offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But the court also said the child support order of $20 a week -
the boy's weekly allowance - should be recalculated. It should
consider what the boy, identified in court papers only as S.M. Jr.,
would earn if he could work full time.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father prohibited his son from working full time to
help support S.M. Jr.'s daughter. He said that would interfere with
the boy's schoolwork. S.M. Jr. had been having trouble in school
and was starting to do better, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ordered the boy's father to make up the
difference between the $20 a week allowance and the boy's earning
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ''...having limited S.M. Jr.'s ability to earn income, S.M. Sr.
must be responsible for the consequences of his own decision,'' the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Uliase, the attorney for the defendants, said her
clients asked her not to comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1813 </TRAILER>
