<HEADLINE> ''Crustaceans in Paradise'' wins 25th annual crab beauty pageant  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - ''Crustaceans in Paradise,'' two
elaborately dressed Jimmy Buffett-loving hermit crabs lounging on a
tiny beach beneath pipe-cleaner palm trees, captured top honors
Wednesday in the 25th annual Miss Crustacean beauty pageant for
crabs.
</P>
<P>
   The entry, submitted by 10 young cousins, bested 30 other
similarly outlandish creations to win the pageant, held annually in
this southern New Jersey resort as a parody of the Miss America
Pageant.
</P>
<P>
   The winning crabs were presented on an old children's billiards
table that was converted into a miniature island paradise, replete
with sandy beach, a thatched hut made of wooden sticks, an
''ocean'' made of stapled blue garlands and tiny umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   The two crabs wore flowered shirts and miniature pith helmets as
they scurried around on the sand. The 2-by-3-foot entry was carried
by the cousins, who were decked out in hula dresses, flowered
shirts and multi-colored ''Parrothead'' hats inspired by Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   The creators were Meghann Dougherty, 13, Kevin Dougherty, 11, of
Flourtown, Pa., and their cousins Ryan Moore, 12, and Jeffrey
Moore, 14, of Columbia, Pa., and Alessandra Cerchione, 10, Gregory
Cerchione, 8, and Francesca Cercione, 13, of Brooklyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   After the winner was announced, one of the crabs took the
traditional victory walk, making its way down a miniature runway
before the handlers were presented with the Cucumber Rind Cup,
''the symbol of crustacean comeliness'' given to each year's
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other entries: Crab Salad, giant salad bowl with a
hermit crab inside; Vote Republican - George Crab Bush, which had a
red, white and blue GOP convention theme; and New Jersey Deviled
Crab, which was a cardboard box decorated to look like a hockey
arena and carried by four small children wearing devil's horns and
New Jersey Devils hockey jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is really, really big,'' said the city's municipal
publicist, Mark Soifer, who dreamed up the event in 1975 as a
publicity stunt and has watched it achieve worldwide notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   It was once a question on ''Jeopardy'' and has received coverage
from U.S. News &AMP; World Report, the Wall Street Journal and CNN in
years past.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, there was only one television camera on
the beach to cover the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it weren't for the Republican National Convention, there'd
be more media here today. But we won't quibble about it,'' said
Soifer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 1830 </TRAILER>
