<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 81; Nasdaq Ends Down 27  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks moved higher Wednesday,
rallying in the wake of more encouraging news that left investors
optimistic that the economy is indeed slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 80.58 at 10,687.53.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 0.60 at 1,438.70 but the
Nasdaq composite index gave back some earlier gains and closed down
27.06 at 3,658.46.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rate sensitive Dow stocks surged after the Conference
Board reported that its leading economic indicators were unchanged
in June.
</P>
<P>
   An important gauge of future economic activity, the Index of
Leading Economic Indicators held steady at 106 in June. If the
forecast is accurate, the numbers would mean a break from rapid
economic growth for the rest of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government reported that U.S. home sales
declined in June to their lowest level in two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors viewed both economic reports as signs that the Federal
Reserve Board's strategy of raising interest rates during the past
year has been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rally came right after the numbers were released and the
feeling is that there's a relatively good chance that the Fed's not
going to do anything'' at its next meeting Aug. 22, said Tom
Gallagher, head of U.S. equity markets for CIBC World Markets in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three other reports also indicated that the economy
is easing after a decade of explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   Banking stocks advanced Wednesday on the belief that lending and
underwriting activity of stocks and bonds will stay healthy if
interest rates remain stable based on the positive economic
indicators. Lehman Brothers rose $5.75 to $118.50, and Merrill
Lynch rose $1.75 to $127.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher noted that Wednesday's rally was confined to a limited
number of stocks, which he attributed to caution on the part of
investors who remain hopeful -- but not certain -- that the Fed will
leave interest rates alone.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, a handful of widely held stocks, including Cisco
Systems and Dell Computer, fell on fears that revenues may decline
in the second half of 2000. Cisco fell $2.25 to $60.938, and Dell
lost $2 to $39.563.
</P>
<P>
   Those long-range fears helped drag down the broader technology
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Some lesser known technology stocks surged after reporting
better-than-expected second-quarter earnings. For example,
technology consulting company Sapient Corp. rose $16.938 to
$120.813 after reporting second-quarter earnings of 23 cents a
share, excluding one-time expenditures. The figure beat analyst
expectations by 3 cents. In addition, the company announced a
two-for-one stock split.
</P>
<P>
   And Protein Design Labs rose $15.141 to $147.75 after reporting
earnings of 23 cents a share, beating analysts' predictions of 18
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues were ahead of decliners by a 5 to 4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.18 billion
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace of 1.11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.45 at 500.22.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.66 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.46 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.18 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 1836 </TRAILER>
