<HEADLINE> Atlantic City tries again to bask in spotlight of GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - Gamely trying to attract attention of
their own, Atlantic City tourism leaders set up ''the world's
largest craps table'' Wednesday in hopes of luring media who are in
the region to cover the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   For a second day, though, they failed.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-by-21-foot table, which was equipped with 1-foot square
foam dice and a seven-foot rake, was set up on the Boardwalk near
Park Place. Passers-by were invited to take their chance at winning
T-shirts, postcards and other prizes provided by casinos, but no
money was wagered.
</P>
<P>
   No convention-covering media types came, either. The same was
true Tuesday, when the Atlantic City Convention and Visitors
Authority sponsored a nine-hole golf tournament on a makeshift
course on the beach in hopes of luring people from the Philadelphia
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to create some excitement about Atlantic City, do a
little fun, showbiz-kind of thing and capture people's attention,''
said Speros Batistatos, president of the authority.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't bothered by the fact that only local media and
Boardwalk tourists showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not discouraged,'' said Batistatos.
</P>
</TEXT>
