<HEADLINE> Investor must pay legal fees of husband who allegedly tried to kill her </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An investment executive has been ordered to give
her husband money for legal fees despite his being charged with
attempted murder for allegedly bashing her in the head with a
10-pound barbell.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Saxe of the State Supreme Court's Appellate
Division ordered Theresa Havell, 53, to give $215,000 to lawyers
for her husband, Aftab Islam, 59.
</P>
<P>
   New York law says that with few exceptions, fault is not a
factor in dividing marital assets.
</P>
<P>
   Saxe's July 26 order modified a lower court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, State Supreme Court Justice Jacqueline Silbermann
ordered Havell to give Islam $450,000 from his share of their
marital assets. The judge's decision did not explain why Havell -
who founded and runs Havell Capital Management - has control of all
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Havell objected to the disbursement, saying Islam's alleged
attempt to kill her should bar him from sharing their money. But
Silbermann found ''the husband would not be deprived of any
interest in the marital property under the existing case law, and
that the amount requested was essentially (minimal) in light of the
size of the marital estate.'' The judge said the amount was about
4.5 percent of the couples' total assets.
</P>
<P>
   Saxe told lawyers for the estranged couple to submit papers to
the Appellate Division and a full panel of the court will decide
whether Islam should get the rest of the $450,000 he asked for.
</P>
<P>
   Havell's lawyer, Ellen Gesmer, refused to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Islam, free on $1 million bail, is charged with trying to kill
his wife in their East 78th Street home early on April 22, 1999. He
pleaded not guilty and a psychiatric defense.
</P>
<P>
   Havell underwent surgery at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical
Center for skull fractures and other broken bones. Several of her
teeth were knocked out and she needed 100 stitches on her face and
head.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers said Islam, married to Havell for 21 years, told
police he hit his wife after she bit him when he gently stroked her
hair. He blamed the incident on a combination of wine and
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Islam is charged with attempted murder, criminal possession of a
dangerous weapon, and three counts of endangering the welfare of a
child. He allegedly attacked his wife in front of three of their
six children, ages 15, 12 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   His trial is scheduled to start Aug. 21. He faces up to 25 years
in prison if he is convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
