<HEADLINE> State issues severe warnings to 14 nursing homes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - New York state health officials cited 14
nursing homes for serious lapses in care that may have led to the
deaths of several patients.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the reports offer a measure of proof that
New York's Health Department has taken steps to improve its system
for policing nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reports' findings were:
</P>
<P>
   Two residents of the Loretto Geriatric Center in Syracuse
suffocated within a week of one another, both times because the
home failed to address long-standing problems with their care.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state has refused to Loretto of Utica to accept
new patients after it received an ''immediate jeopardy citation''
for more widespread problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Chemung County Nursing Facility ran into trouble after a man
pried the screen off his fourth-floor bedroom window one night in
May and leaped out, causing injuries that ultimately killed him.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the home had seen him trying to escape from the
building before and knew he had threatened suicide two weeks
before, but did not do enough to monitor his condition, inspectors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar problems have been found at a list of other homes from
the countryside south of Rochester to New York City and its
northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Health Department had only 198 people to oversee
2,406 nursing homes, home health care agencies and adult homes.
</P>
<P>
   Department analysts concluded in an internal June 1999 report
that those levels had caused problems ''both of quantity and
quality'' in the state's nursing home enforcement system.
</P>
<P>
   That system was criticized by the U.S. Health Care Financing
Administration, the federal agency that controls the government's
Medicare insurance program, for overlooking serious - and in some
cases life-threatening - problems.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every case in which the federal government spot checks
the state's work, it finds problems that the state should have made
note of but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very clear that they've upped the ante,'' said Nancy
Tucker, the director of nursing facility policy at the New York
Association of Homes and Services for the Aging, an Albany group
that represents hundreds of the state's nonprofit homes. ''The
department is responding to a lot of criticism, which has put a lot
of facilities between a rock and a hard place.''
</P>
<P>
   The nursing homes cited are:
</P>
<P>
   -Kirkhaven Nursing Home, Rochester
</P>
<P>
   -Bethany Nursing Home, Rochester
</P>
<P>
   -Chemung County Nursing Facility, Elmira
</P>
<P>
   -Loretto of Syracuse
</P>
<P>
   -Loretto of Utica
</P>
<P>
   -John E. Andrus Memorial Home, Westchester County
</P>
<P>
   -Hornell Gardens Nursing and Rehabilitation Center
</P>
<P>
   -Northeast Center for Special Care, Lake Katrine
</P>
<P>
   -Victory Lake Nursing Home, New Rochelle
</P>
<P>
   -Throggs Neck Nursing Home, Bronx
</P>
<P>
   -University Nursing Home, Bronx
</P>
<P>
   -Daughters of Jacob Nursing Home, Bronx
</P>
<P>
   -Rutland Nursing Home, Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   -Brooklyn United Methodist Church Home
</P>
</TEXT>
