<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions say strike possible in Verizon talks  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Officials of unions representing more than
85,000 Verizon Communications workers in 12 eastern states say
contract negotiations remain so far apart a strike is possible this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon workers from Maine to Virginia are negotiating for
higher pay, better benefits and improved working conditions. Union
negotiators also are trying to organize wireless workers at
Verizon, formerly known as Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   One union source, discussing the situation on condition of
anonymity, said a strike was ''very possible,'' but talks are
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Responding, Verizon spokesman Steve Marcus said: ''Both sides
are continuing to negotiate in good faith and are working hard to
reach an agreement by the deadline of the current contracts. We are
hopeful that this can be accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was created in June by the merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE Corp. Its wireless operation is its fastest growing division, a
separate company run through a joint venture with Vodafone
AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America represents about 72,500
Verizon workers. The International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers represents 13,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   The union source said none of the major issues posed by union
negotiators has been addressed by Verizon in contract talks that
began June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators moved the talks to Washington on Monday in
anticipation of the 12:01 a.m. EDT Sunday deadline. The union
source said little had been accomplished as of Wednesday afternoon,
however, and a company response on a variety of matters was
awaited.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA this week gave its president, Morton Bahr, authority to
call a strike if the deadline passes without agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dispute was generated by the unions' demand for
member access to new jobs in the wireless operation.
</P>
<P>
   CWA representatives say differences in wages and benefits
between union and nonunion workers are significant. Verizon has
said the company needs flexibility to decide what it pays workers
in the rapidly growing field.
</P>
<P>
   An impasse Sunday could send operators and technicians to the
picket lines and leave 25 million homes and businesses without help
setting up phone services, repairing or installing lines or
figuring out their telephone bills.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon workers in 12 states and the District of Columbia are
represented. The states covered: Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, New York, New Jersey, Delaware,
Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com/home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
