<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fisherman has close encounter with black bear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) - A 200-pound black bear went fishing and
nearly caught the fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Taylor had hooked five smallmouth bass Monday night when he
noticed another hungry mammal looking to relieve the Chemung River
of a few fish.
</P>
<P>
   The bear, fresh from a snack at a neighbor's bird feeder, had
ambled over to the river in southern central New York, most likely
looking for more food as it begins its winter preparations,
according to a scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Bears eat meat and vegetation but aren't predators, said Bruce
Penrod of the state Department of Environmental Conservation. This
bear probably had been fed so often by humans, it had lost its
natural wariness.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, on the other hand, was plenty wary.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first reaction -- just like anybody else's would be -- was
to run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He headed straight into the river, with the bear behind. About
halfway across, the bear got snagged in some brush, allowing the
angler to scramble up a bank to a neighbor's house.
</P>
<P>
   The chase surprised Penrod, who said bears rarely charge humans.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a strong message out of this,'' Penrod said. ''Cease
and desist feeding the bears.''
</P>
<P>
   Elmira is 75 miles southwest of Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
