<DOCNO> APW20000802.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamond Origin Certification Urged  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A year ago nobody talked about ''blood
diamonds.'' Now, the issue of illegally mined diamonds that are
fueling wars across Africa has become a top priority for the
diamond industry, the world's leading powers and the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   A two-day U.N. hearing this week has increased momentum for a
global system to certify the origin of diamonds so dealers can keep
''blood diamonds'' that fuel wars in Sierra Leone, Congo and Angola
off of jewelers' shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole diamond industry has focused on the huge downside to
the industry if the world public turn against conflict diamonds,
and therefore turn against diamonds,'' Britain's U.N. Ambassador
Jeremy Greenstock said Wednesday. ''They're also genuinely
concerned not to be part of fueling a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting two weeks ago in Antwerp, Belgium, the
international diamond industry adopted strict new measures that
track diamonds from mines in conflict areas to the jewelry store
and announced a ban on dealers that buy or sell ''blood diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The push to stop ''blood diamonds'' started with a ban last year
on diamonds sold by Angola's UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, the Security Council banned the purchase of
Sierra Leone diamonds without a government certificate in a bid to
strangle the ability of the rebel Revolutionary United Front to
finance the civil war, which has killed and maimed tens of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds also play a role in fueling the conflict in Congo, but
there is no ban affecting that country.
</P>
<P>
   At this week's U.N. hearing, Sierra Leone's Minister for Mineral
Resources Mohammed Deen presented a new government certificate
developed with the United States, Britain, Belgium, Israel and the
Diamond High Council in Antwerp. He also announced new procedures
for the mining and export of rough diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh's U.N. Ambassador Anwarul Chowdhury, who chairs the
Security Council committee monitoring sanctions against Sierra
Leone, said it will meet by early next week to examine the proposed
certification procedures. If approved, they should be immediately
implemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leone proposal has now emerged as a possible model
for global certification of diamonds, after it won overwhelming
approval from the representatives from the diamond industry,
governments, and voluntary organizations who attended the U.N.
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''A global regime is necessary if we want to get rid of the
conflict diamonds,'' Chowdhury said Tuesday at the close of the
hearing Tuesday, which was organized by the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
   At last month's meeting of the seven major industrial powers and
Russia in Okinawa, Britain and Russia announced that they will host
a conference of about 30 diamond producing countries by the end of
September in Moscow to establish an international legal basis for
regulating the diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   The conference will be followed by the introduction of a General
Assembly resolution in the autumn to start a formal treaty
negotiating process under U.N. auspices, British officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A five-member panel just named by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan will work with the diamond industry in perfecting
arrangements for a certificate of origin, Greenstock, the British
ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that the diamond industry will respond by making this
certificate of origin regime universal so that everybody selling a
diamond has to show a certificate that they got it legitimately,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same panel is to collect information on possible violations
of the ''blood diamond'' ban and report them to the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said the message about the
deadly effects of ''blood diamonds'' must now get to the buying
public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the world has only recently begun to recognize
that diamonds, the most beautiful of all gem stones, are also a
deadly component of some of the worst conflicts on earth,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
