<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State institute gets Appalachian grant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Institute for Entrepreneurship has been
awarded $170,000 to bring its educational program to 800 students
in the 14 counties that make up the state's Appalachian region.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Youth Entrepreneurial Program features a 30- to
50-hour online instruction system that teaches students how to
start, run and expand their own business. Activities will begin in
September at high schools in Allegany, Broome, Cattaraugus,
Chautauqua, Chemung, Chenango, Cortland, Delaware, Otsego,
Schoharie, Schuyler, Steuben, Tioga and Tompkins counties.
</P>
<P>
   The program will take place from January through December 2001
</P>
<P>
   The grant from the federal Appalachian Regional Commission will
allow schools to access the program free of charge. It includes
teacher training and student internships at local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, about 30 schools and 800 students will participate in
the 16-month program. School district may still apply.
</P>
<P>
   The Appalachian Regional Commission was established in 1965 to
support economic and social development in the country's
Appalachian Region.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Entrepreneurship is a nonprofit agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
