<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nilsson Released by Japanese Team  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Nilsson hopes he hits better at the Sydney Olympics than
he did in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, an All-Star catcher with the Milwaukee Brewers in 1999,
was released by the Chunichi Dragons after a season-long slump that
saw him sent to the Japanese minors.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, 30, asked the Dragons to cancel his one-year contract,
and they immediately obliged, team spokesman Testsuo Ishiguro said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt his performance wasn't as good as expected,'' said
Ishiguro.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson hit only .180 with one home run and eight RBIs for the
Dragons. He was sent down to the minors in late April.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Nilsson was bothered by lower back pain. The
Australian native returned home for a short time to be checked.
</P>
<P>
   Ishiguro said Nilsson planned to travel back to the United
States, though no timetable was set for his trip.
</P>
<P>
   It is still expected Nilsson will play for Australia in the
Olympics. There is a reasonable chance he'll be back in the
American majors next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not surprised,'' Milwaukee outfielder Marquis Grissom
said. ''That's a big adjustment. It's a different kind of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope he comes back over here because he's definitely a big
league player. He could sign with us again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson batted .309 with 21 home runs and 62 RBIs for Milwaukee
last season. He was a lifetime .284 hitter with 105 homers in an
eight-year career, spent entirely with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, however, left the majors after making it clear he
wanted to play for his homeland in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Games start in September. This is the first time
American professional teams will let players compete in the
Olympics, but clubs are not letting their top stars take part.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson signed with Chunichi in mid-January for a reported $2
million. As part of his deal with the Dragons, he was going to be
allowed to play for Australia in the Olympics and then become a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a dream come true for me. This is what I wanted,''
Nilsson said when he agreed to terms in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, the first Australian major leaguer ever to play
Japanese ball, was expected to post big numbers for Chunichi. He
was popular at the start and became known by the nickname
''Dingo.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite his big salary -- by Japanese standards -- and big
numbers for the Brewers, he got off to a slow start and never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure he could have gotten a job here, so I'm not even sure
why he went over there,'' Milwaukee pitcher Jeff D'Amico said.
''The guy can hit, so I'm surprised he did so poorly over there.
That's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   A left-handed hitting catcher with pop, Nilsson likely would
have no trouble finding a job in the majors. He made $5.7 million
with the Brewers in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2026 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0188 </DOCNO>
