<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Rains Kill At Least 45  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Five days of heavy rains that triggered
deadly mudslides and flooding in northeastern Brazil eased
Wednesday, but authorities said the death toll rose to 45.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more in Pernambuco and Alagoas states were also driven
from their homes by the rising waters, bringing the number seeking
shelter in schools, churches and with friends to about 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Globo TV showed entire towns partially submerged in water. Other
images showed people wading through waist high water trying to
salvage whatever they could.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was perhaps the worst natural disaster ever to hit
Pernambuco,'' civil defense official Carlos D'Alburquerque said by
phone from the state capital of Recife, about 1,300 miles northeast
of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Roads, highways and bridges have been washed away and the only
way to rescue countless others who are isolated is by boat and
helicopter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dead were caught by huge mudslides that plowed
through mostly poor homes perched precariously on hills.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest deaths, 18 people were killed in Pernambuco,
D'Alburquerque said without elaborating. About 50,000 there have
fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighboring Alagoas, the mudslides that ravaged hillside
shantytowns killed 27 people and drove 52,000 from their homes,
said Soraya Alves Leite, a spokeswoman for the state government.
</P>
<P>
   The rains let up on Wednesday but both D'Alburquerque and Leite
said the skies were overcast and more downpours were expected.
</P>
<P>
   Military troops joined in the rescue effort, retrieving trapped
people and distributing food, water and medicine to the homeless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2028 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One man arrested in 1999 death of graduate student  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - More than a year after a graduate student was
fatally stabbed in the back with a 10-inch kitchen knife as she
walked to her Brooklyn apartment, police on Wednesday announced an
arrest in the case.
</P>
<P>
   David Jamison, 27, of Brooklyn, has been charged with
first-degree murder, first-degree robbery and criminal possession
of a weapon in Amy Watkins' death. Police also questioned two other
men in the case at the 77th Precinct in Brooklyn, but did not
immediately charge them with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison was picked up for questioning Wednesday thanks to
several tips to police, including some from the Crime Stoppers hot
line. He was previously arrested for selling drugs, petit larceny
and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   A police source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Jamison and two other men saw Watkins walk by the restaurant they
were in on March 8, 1999, and decided she would be an easy robbery
target. Watkins apparently struggled with her attacker and she was
stabbed once, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Watkins, the victim's father, said in a telephone
interview from his Manhattan home that he was completely surprised
when police called him about 1 p.m. Wednesday to tell them about
the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought someday something would happen, but I really didn't
have a lot of hope,'' he said. He expressed gratitude to the police
for never giving up on the case.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter's death horrified the city and her neighbors in
Prospect Heights, a quiet neighborhood of gentrified brownstones a
short subway ride from Manhattan. Her death came at a time when the
city was in the midst of a dramatic decrease in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, 26 and from Kansas, was studying for her masters in
social work, counseling battered women and working with children as
an intern at the New Settlement Community Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   She had taken the subway from the Bronx, where she organized a
meeting for parents about their children's reading scores. She was
attacked as she walked home from the subway station, after stopping
for some groceries shortly before 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   She was unconscious when passers-by found her on the sidewalk -
some residents said they heard a woman scream. Watkins lived with a
roommate in an apartment building about two blocks from where she
was stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Illinois but raised in Topeka, Kan., and
graduated from the University of Kansas. She moved to New York in
1997 after living briefly in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was a second-year graduate student at Hunter College's
School of Social Work, had an internship at the center and had
started working there in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She was buried in suburban St. Louis, where her mother, Margaret
Tafoya, and her stepfather, John Tafoya, live. Lawrence Watkins
teaches at Dominican Academy in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 2030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
