<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Pinochet's Immunity Revoked  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's Supreme Court has stripped Gen.
Augusto Pinochet of immunity from prosecution, paving the way for
the former dictator to stand trial on human rights charges, a
lawyer and an official close to Pinochet said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The court refused to publicly release its ruling. But lawyer
Hugo Gutierrez, who represents one of the plaintiffs accusing the
84-year-old general of rights abuses, said he had ''fully
confirmed'' the Supreme Court justices removed Pinochet's immunity
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the Pinochet Foundation, a private group of
Pinochet supporters and former aides, also said it was clear
Pinochet had lost.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet faces 154 criminal complaints stemming from human
rights abuses during his 1973-90 dictatorship, but he cannot be
tried unless his congressional legal immunity is removed.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court stripped Pinochet of that immunity earlier this
year, and Pinochet appealed. The Supreme Court's 20 justices met
for four hours Tuesday to hear the appeal but did not release a
decision afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The justices ''maintain our agreement not to give any
information whatsoever until the legal ruling has been written and
signed by all of us,'' Chief Justice Hernan Alvarez said Wednesday.
He said an announcement could come next week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the official secrecy, Chilean media reports said the
court turned down Pinochet's appeal, and many said the vote was
11-9 against Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official tally, 3,190 people were killed during
Pinochet's regime, and more than 1,000 remain missing after being
arrested during those years.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman, who is probing complaints from relatives of
the missing, is seeking Pinochet's trial in one of the most
notorious incidents -- the so-called ''caravan of death.'' That was
the name given to a military squad that summarily executed 72
political prisoners in several cities shortly after Pinochet's
bloody 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Chilean military made an unprecedented promise
to help determine what happened to the more than 1,000 dissidents
who disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   That pledge appeared to begin yielding results Wednesday, when
Methodist Bishop Enrique Vilches delivered to the government what
he described as information on 780 of the missing. He said the
information was received by members of his church from former
military and secret police officials.
</P>
<P>
   Details on the information Vilches turned over were not
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The military made its promise to help unravel the fates of the
missing in an agreement with government officials and human rights
activists. The agreement included a guarantee of anonymity for
those coming forward with information.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean exiles and human rights groups in Britain celebrated the
report. Pinochet left Britain in March after he was declared
mentally unfit to be extradited to Spain on torture charges, ending
a 16-month legal saga.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is wonderful news for Chile and for all the people who
suffered so much under his regime,'' said Carlos Reyas, spokesman
for Chile Democratico and Chileans in Exile. ''We are hoping that
this will open the door and get our missing ones back to their
families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2034 </TRAILER>
