<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans take stand against landfill near memorial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AVA, N.Y. - A group of veterans is camped out in a memorial
forest here, a peaceful protest against a proposed landfill a
quarter-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Willson, along with a group of veterans who call themselves
''Veterans Defending Our Memorial Forest,'' is fighting a landfill
proposed by the Oneida-Herkimer Solid Waste Management Authority.
Part of the landfill would be located about 1,400 feet from the
edge of the 800-acre Oneida County-owned forest, 42 miles northeast
of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Vietnam, I didn't know what I was fighting for. Here, I
do,'' said the 56-year-old veteran who proposed to his wife about
30 years ago in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Willson was one of about 50 local veterans who have taken a
stand against the proposed landfill. The veterans have camped out
on the site since Sunday in protest and expect to stay until at
least Aug. 10 when the state Department of Environmental
Conservation conducts two public hearings on the issue. The DEC has
the authority to site the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Authority board member Gerald C. Brodock, himself a veteran,
told the Utica Observer-Dispatch: ''I understand what (the
veterans) position is, but I don't agree with it. I don't believe
having a landfill that far away would desecrate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Martin, a retired Marine, said the tallest trees surrounding
the monument are about 60- to 70-feet tall, or about a third as
tall as the proposed landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our memorial will be dwarfed by garbage,'' Martin said.
''Trash will blow onto the memorial. Rats and vermin will run over
this sacred land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-02-00 2039 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
