<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers 5, Angels 3  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Brian Moehler held Anaheim scoreless on
six hits through the first seven innings and Bobby Higginson hit a
two-run homer as the Detroit Tigers defeated the Angels 5-3 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moehler (7-7) was charged with one run and struck out five. He
walked his only batter leading off Anaheim's three-run eighth
inning before he was replaced by C.J. Nitkowski -- despite throwing
only 84 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Moehler struggled in his previous start at Texas on July 28,
giving up 10 runs on 11 hits in 2 2-3 innings. The right-hander
yielded at least 11 hits in three of his previous four starts. He
worked with runners on base in each of the first six innings, but
allowed a runner past second only once.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Tim Salmon was 4-for-4 for the second time in the
three-game series, in which he was 10-for-12 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson gave Detroit a 2-0 lead in the first with his 21st
homer on a 2-1 pitch from Ken Hill (5-7). Detroit capitalized on
Hill's throwing error, coming on a sacrifice bunt by Shane Halter,
to score three runs in the fifth. Former Angel Damion Easley hit a
two-run single and Dean Palmer made it 5-0 with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had an RBI single off Doug Brocail in the eighth,
followed by Garret Anderson's two-run double over the outstretched
glove of a leaping Higginson at the left field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Jones pitched the ninth for his AL-leading 31st save in 33
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is winless in his last five consecutive starts. The
right-hander gave up five runs on seven hits in six innings, while
walking three and striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels couldn't score any runs, left fielder Darin
Erstad and Adam Kennedy made sparkling defensive plays. Erstad's
diving catch in the second robbed Halter of extra bases, while
second baseman Kennedy fielded Juan Gonzalez's grounder up the
middle and made a nice backhanded flip to Benji Gil for the force
on Higginson.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Anaheim C Matt Walbeck threw out two Detroit runners after
the Tigers were 18 of 19 in stolen-base attempts. ... Hill allowed
a homer for the sixth straight game and his ERA hasn't been under
6.00 since his third start of the season. ... Juan Encarnacion
became only the second batter hit by Hill in 77 2-3 innings. ...
Detroit improved to 42-17 when scoring four or more runs. ...
Starting Friday in Cleveland, Anaheim plays 32 of its remaining 53
on the road. ... RHP Matt Wise made his major league debut for the
Angels in the seventh, a day after being promoted from Triple-A
Edmonton. ... Angels All-Star 3B Troy Glaus, who batted only .194
in July, did not benefit from getting a day off Tuesday. He
grounded out all four times up, including a grounder to shortstop
that ended Anaheim's eighth-inning rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2039 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
