<HEADLINE> State investigation clears Escambia deputies in couple's deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) - A state investigation has cleared
sheriff's deputies of wrongdoing in a shootout with a lawyer and
his ex-wife, who killed her husband, then herself before both were
hit by police bullets, autopsies indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The murder-suicide occurred during a gun battle with Escambia
County deputies in a tire store's parking lot following a car chase
on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Haberski, 40, a former FBI agent, and Jennifer Haberski,
29, were being sought as suspects in a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Curtis Golden pronounced the case closed Tuesday
after reviewing an investigative report by the Florida Department
of Law Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Haberski left a note to his family in his car. He wrote
that ''Jennifer was not my downfall,'' expressed his love for his
family and ended with the post-script: ''Remember the movie rights
for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an implication that it was written in the
contemplation of death,'' Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   Escambia deputies have been involved in shoot-outs that have
resulted in the deaths of nine suspects, not counting the
Haberskis, over the past five years. The U.S. Justice Department
and FBI are investigating the shooting of an unarmed black suspect
last year for possible civil rights law violations.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jim Lowman said he was satisfied with Golden's
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to let the citizens and our officers know we didn't
fire the fatal shots,'' Lowman said. ''We never make any
assumptions until we get the full report, but we thought from the
preliminary investigation that it would turn out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents of the Federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
also were looking for the couple on the day of the shooting for
questioning about an arson fire two days earlier at a Pensacola
strip club partly owned by Justin Haberski.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies got a report that four people were being robbed near a
shopping mall. During a 13-minute chase that followed, Jennifer
Haberski stood up through the car's sunroof and shot at pursing
officers with a 9 mm semiautomatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had recently moved to New Orleans, where ATF agents
had spotted their car after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Haberski was with the FBI in New York from 1984 through 1990
under name Stanley G. Haberski. His sister and parents live in
Panama City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
