<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls' Krause Has Little To Say  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- On a day he's been waiting almost two
years for, Chicago Bulls general manager Jerry Krause had nothing
to say.
</P>
<P>
   Or very little, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   After being turned down by the top players available this
summer, Krause introduced the one free agent he was able to lure
and then quickly got out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   He left Ron Mercer and coach Tim Floyd on Wednesday afternoon,
saying, ''My phone is loaded right now. ... I've got phone calls
that have got to take me up to that phone room.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder Krause didn't want to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Michael Jordan's retirement and an aging team, Krause
and chairman Jerry Reinsdorf gutted the Bulls after they won their
sixth championship in eight years. Their hope was to stockpile
draft picks and get as far below the salary cap as they could so
they could lure marquee free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago went a horrid 30-102 as the team looked toward this
summer, when Tim Duncan, Grant Hill, Tracy McGrady and Eddie Jones
would be available.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls began the free agent chase with almost $20 million in
salary cap room, enough that Krause was confident they could sign
two ''full-boat'' players. Only Orlando had similar money
available.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of flocking to Chicago, the top free agents went
elsewhere. Duncan stayed in San Antonio. Orlando is expected to
announce the formal signings of Hill and McGrady on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones convinced the Charlotte Hornets to send him to Miami in a
blockbuster sign-and-trade deal. Even Tim Thomas, who didn't start
for the Bucks last season, turned the Bulls down, opting instead to
stay in Milwaukee for less money.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer, who averaged 16.9 points last season, might have been on
the Bulls' wish list, but he was far from their first choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think he is really going to help our team,'' Krause said.
''This is a step forward for us. This is the first step forward
we're taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercer, the sixth overall pick in 1997, signed a deal worth $27
million over four years. That still leaves the Bulls with plenty of
money, but the number of free agents is dwindling quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a matter of just getting it started. Anything can
happen,'' Mercer said. ''We're not out of the recruiting process.
Something could happen tomorrow, something could happen a couple of
weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's the exciting part,'' he added. ''Things are
only going to go up. We're not going to go backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercer said he wasn't concerned that so many other free agents
turned the Bulls down. He also isn't bothered by the animosity some
former players -- namely Jordan and Scottie Pippen -- have for Krause
and the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not any of my business,'' Mercer said. ''That's the way I
look at it. That's those guys and when they were here. I have no
comment on that because it has nothing to do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also isn't put off by the prospect of playing for a
rebuilding team.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a challenge I want,'' he said. ''I'm glad to do it.
I'm glad to be here and take on that challenge. I want to be the
future and take this team to the future -- and repeat the past.''
</P>
<P>
   While McGrady expressed concern about the burden of replacing
Jordan, Mercer said he doesn't even think about that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't look at it as trying to come in and fill Michael
Jordan's shoes. That's not my job. I can't do that,'' he said.
''This is a totally different team. This is not the Bulls of the
'90s. This is the rebuilding Bulls. And that's how I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercer, who helped Kentucky reach the Final Four in each of his
two college seasons, will be playing for his fourth team in as many
years. He was drafted by the Boston Celtics, traded to Denver and
then dealt to Orlando last season.
</P>
<P>
   He's tired of moving, and said he was looking for a place where
he could settle down. He knew Chicago was the right place when
Floyd took him out for a round of golf during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did the simplest things, things that I liked,'' he said.
''That's why I'm here today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2055 </TRAILER>
