<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Get Single-Game Tickets  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Less than six weeks before a referendum
on a sales tax in Brown County to help renovate Lambeau Field, the
Green Bay Packers gave county residents hope they might someday get
to enjoy the improvements the tax would fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers announced a plan Wednesday to distribute 40,000
tickets to non-season ticket-holders each season, beginning in
2003. Under the plan, 4,000 tickets for each of 10 games will be
awarded by lottery to eligible Brown County households.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ''may change some minds,'' Packers president Bob Harlan
said. ''What's more important is I honestly think we're doing what
we should be doing. I feel a strong obligation to the residents of
Brown County.''
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1957, Lambeau Field has been sold out for every Packers
game since 1960, and the team's waiting list for season tickets has
nearly 60,000 names on it.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 80,000 households in Brown County would be
eligible for the single-game tickets. Packers fans living outside
the county won't be allowed to enter the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The team hasn't made available single-game tickets in four
decades, but Harlan said the franchise's concern for the community
-- not a politically judicious sense of timing -- was behind
Wednesday's announcement. The referendum on the half percent sales
tax is Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to find a way to reach out to the fans of this
community,'' Harlan said. ''It's important to show the fans what we
want to do for them right now, not years down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlan announced the plan at the home of Kevin and Amy Gille,
two Packers fans who are neither season ticket-holders nor team
shareholders, yet still could see a game under the team's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's important for every generation to be able to get
inside the stadium and see the Packers,'' Kevin Gille said. ''The
team is a big part of our community.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the announcement was timed to push the sales tax
toward passage, Harlan said the Packers were merely responding to
requests from citizens who wanted to know the team's plans for the
expanded seating that would be added to Lambeau if the $295 million
renovation plan is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan said the Packers have heard repeatedly from lawmakers,
taxpayers and fans who don't attend games that more fans should be
eligible to see games if public tax dollars are used to help
finance the stadium's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Steven Donarski of Citizens for Sensible Taxation, a
leading opposition group to the Packers' plan, were not immediately
returned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Any county resident who's at least 18 years old would register
once for the single-game tickets for an indefinite number of
upcoming seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers will hold registrations for the tickets on the
Lambeau Field concourse on the weekends of Aug. 12-13 and Aug.
19-20 -- even though the tickets won't be available for three more
years.
</P>
<P>
   Packers ticket director Mark Wagner said the team will take
special steps to prevent residents from scalping the tickets,
including a special stamp on the tickets' faces.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want this to be a moneymaker for anybody,'' Wagner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers want to add 6,000 additional seats to the top of the
Lambeau Field bowl. Of those extra seats, 2,000 will be given to
people on the waiting list, while the remaining 4,000 will be used
for single-game seats.
</P>
<P>
   The tickets will be awarded throughout the stadium, not just on
the top rows of seating, Harlan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''For all the support our friends and neighbors have given us
for so many years, they deserve those tickets,'' Harlan said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay Packers http://www.packers.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
