<HEADLINE> Lockhart, Letterman Talk Politics  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton gets along just fine with
the guy he beat in 1992 -- no joke, White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart assured David Letterman Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any enmity between the two presidents? Letterman asked
Lockhart on CBS's ''The Late Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, the president did beat him in 1992,'' Lockhart observed
dryly. ''He had to move. He had to pack, move out. But other than
that, they're fine. They get along very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and former President Bush have feuded recently after
Clinton mocked Texas Gov. George W. Bush's credentials to be
president, saying ''My daddy was president. I owned a baseball
team. They like me down there.'' The senior Bush said if Clinton
continued to talk that way ''then I'm going to tell the nation what
I think about him as a human being and a person.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush was an easy target for Clinton, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president went out and poked a little fun at
George W. Bush, which is not a hard thing to do,'' Lockhart said.
''His father, being a father, wanted to defend him and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   On another political note, Letterman asked Lockhart to help the
show arrange a debate between the younger Bush and Vice President
Al Gore. Gore has accepted the offer; Bush hasn't replied, which
has spawned repeated ribbing from Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart confessed that Clinton was a ''little nervous'' before
his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for a Senate seat
from New York, appeared on the Letterman show late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''To make it in New York you've got to come and sit in this
chair and stand up and be able to walk out without assistance,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
