<HEADLINE> German Police Question Bomb Suspect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Police investigating a bomb attack
that injured 10 immigrants from the former Soviet Union said
Wednesday they were questioning a suspect in the case.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutor Johannes Mocken said the suspect had not been
linked to the rightist scene in the past, but that recent
indications had hardened suspicions against him as a possible
suspect in the July 27 train station bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Mocken said the suspect, the owner of a sports and security
items business near where the bombing took place, did have a past
record of violations. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor urged caution at jumping to conclusions,
saying ''of course we must follow up on this lead and all other
leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Mocken said that after questioning of the suspect and evaluation
of what was found in a search of buildings near the station, a
decision would be made on whether he should be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokeswoman declined to say whether the lead had
clarified if the bombing was motivated by anti-Semitism or
anti-foreigner sentiment. The fact that all the victims were
foreigners, and six of them Jewish, have raised fears that it was
carried out by far-right extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they have been bombarded with new tips from the
public after the reward for information was raised to $60,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
