<HEADLINE> K.D. Williams Tries To Fill LB Hole  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Earlier in the week, K.D. Williams wasn't
sure why the Green Bay Packers wanted him. Now he knows.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of opportunity here for a good linebacker,''
Williams said Wednesday after working out with the Packers, who
acquired him in a trade with New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of good players here, but there's no definite
starters and reserves and guys who won't make the team. Everybody's
got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Packers currently stand with a linebacking
corps that could be among the NFL's weakest this season. Of last
year's three starters, only Bernardo Harris will play when Green
Bay opens its preseason schedule against the New York Jets on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams, the team's leading tackler last season before
tearing a knee ligament on Nov. 1, won't play until at least the
regular season opener on Sept. 3, and could be out much longer. The
third starter, George Koonce, was released in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Taking their places are rookies, career backups and castoffs
from other teams. K.D. Williams, who impressed Green Bay as a
member of the Raiders in last year's regular season opener, is the
latest name added to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're putting a lot of guys in position to make this team as a
linebacker,'' coach Mike Sherman said. ''We're going to let them
decide on the field who wants to make the plays at that position.
It will be a process that lasts all the way up to the first game of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams wasn't sure he wanted to leave the Saints when they
traded him. After playing in the CFL, getting chances with four NFL
teams and spending a season in NFL Europe -- with a stint as a
skycap at the Tampa airport in between -- he thought he had a good
shot at making the Saints' roster.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that (the trade) has happened, I feel good about it,''
Williams said. ''I think I can make an impact here.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is enjoying a decent training camp, but none of the other
linebackers has been overly impressive. Sherman plans to give every
linebacker on the roster ample chance to impress him during the
four preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be decided on the field, that's all I can say,'' Sherman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Na'il Diggs has shown potential, particularly as a
run-stopper, but is still raw. Another rookie, Eugene McCaslin, has
caught the eyes of the coaches with his athleticism, but also has
much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Jude Waddy -- who took over Brian Williams' starting spot last
season after the injury -- is still learning his expanded role in
the defense. Though he's considered undersized for an NFL
linebacker, he is also adjusting his physical game after gaining 10
pounds in the weight room during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''I realize I need to step up in this defense, particularly with
Brian out,'' Waddy said. ''I'm trying to take a lot of
responsibility on myself to learn and to lead out there on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Harris played just nine games in the last two seasons
with the Dolphins because of injuries and inconsistency, yet he
entered training camp as the top candidate to take Koonce's
starting spot. He hasn't stood out so far in camp, but that may
change once the preseason schedule starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like to get in games, because that's where I shine,'' Harris
said. ''You can't tell everything about a player from practice. I
like to get in a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
