<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressEds: Dollar amounts are in Canadian dollars
By The Associated Press:
Oil Slick Slows Progress to British Columbia Town
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHETWYND, British Columbia (AP) -- This northeastern British
Columbia resource town earned a brief reprieve Wednesday in its
fight to prepare for the onslaught of a massive oil spill on the
Pine River.
</P>
<P>
   Environment officials tracking the 21-kilometer-long slick now
estimate it won't reach Chetwynd until Thursday, 24 hours later
than first thought.
</P>
<P>
   Three booms were stretched across the river upstream from the
town to contain the million-litre spill from a ruptured pipeline,
but authorities say it's inevitable some oil will reach Chetwynd's
water intake pipe.
</P>
<P>
   The delay gives the town more precious time to fill up its
reservoir with untainted water.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 people, employees of the Pembina Pipeline Corp., were
working to contain and mop up the spill, said Alex Dabrowski, a
spokesman for the British Columbia Environment Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Three booms were flung across the 10-metre-wide river at
different points and trucks with vacuum pumps were trying to skim
off the oil, so far with undetermined success, Dabrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The river is the source of water for 4,000 residents of Chetwynd
and its outlying area.
------
Anti-Nuke Activists Demand Ottawa call Off Russian Airlift
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Anti-nuclear activists fearing a potential
radioactive disaster want a proposed Russia-to-Canada airlift of
weapons-grade plutonium to be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government of Canada has a responsibility to consult the
public,'' said Gordon Edwards, spokesman for the Canadian Coalition
for Nuclear Responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   His group joined several other critics Wednesday to demand that
the shipment be stopped or delayed until there are independent
public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   They fear a crash and subsequent fire could release deadly
plutonium dust -- a concern one nuclear official laughed off.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is ''wrong-headed'' to support disarming nuclear weapons
in the United States and Russia by seeing how well plutonium can be
burned in nuclear reactors, said the activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's about propping up the nuclear industry'' at needless risk
to Canada, said Kristen Ostling, spokeswoman for the Campaign for
Nuclear Phaseout.
</P>
<P>
   Atomic Energy of Canada Ltd. (AECL) submitted a plan Friday to
fly plutonium-laden fuel made from surplus Russian warheads to a
Candu reactor at Chalk River, Ontario, near Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   It would be used with an earlier shipment of U.S. plutonium in
reactor tests expected to take about three years.
------
Reform School Staffer Denied Parole
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- One of the dozens of victims sexually
abused by convicted pedophile Karl Toft was relieved and grateful
Wednesday after the National Parole Board denied Toft's request for
early release.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's the best thing the government did so far for
Toft,'' said the victim, who identified himself as Mark McGinnis.
''He's not dead yet. So he's not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis, who saw Toft for the first time in 16 years, had swore
at his former tormenter as he walked into the hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hey, Toftie! You should be in . . . jail,'' McGinnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Toft was a staff member at the Youth Training Centre in
Kingsclear, New Brunswick In 1992 he was sentenced to 13 years in
prison for 34 sex crimes, committed over three decades, against
boys in his care.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1999 he was sent to the Phoenix program for sex offenders
and confined to an Edmonton mental hospital. He was seeking release
into the community to begin the program's second stage.
</P>
<P>
   After an entire morning of detailed questions about Toft's
sexual patterns, the three-member board ruled that he didn't have
an adequate plan to battle his pedophiliac temptations.
</P>
<P>
   The board was particularly troubled by Toft's inability to
remember some of his more vicious assaults, said board member
Claire Carefoot.
------
Toronto To Send Garbage To Ontario Mine
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- In a move that infuriated many, the largest city
in Canada decided Wednesday it wants to ship millions of tonnes of
trash by trainload to an abandoned mine in Ontario's north.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of debate in city council Tuesday and Wednesday and
an impassioned plea in support of the plan by Toronto Mayor Mel
Lastman, councillors voted to ship 1.3 million tonnes of garbage
annually to an abandoned open-pit mine near Kirkland Lake, Ontario,
a town of 10,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the garbage will ever see its way to Ontario's north,
however, remained in question.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Belanger, of the Against the Adams Mine Campaign, vowed
to step up the battle against the garbage plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are prepared for a long fight and we promise Mr. Lastman
will get a bad reputation as Canada's toxic bad boy,'' he said in a
reference to Lastman's Bad Boy furniture chain.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Coun. Jack Layton, a vocal opponent of the 12-year-old
proposal, said he's hoping the opinions of councillors will change
by October when they ratify Wednesday's vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
