<HEADLINE> Notes from Wednesday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Blue Jays-Athletics:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO: RF Raul Mondesi went to Florida to seek a third opinion
on his ligament problems in his right elbow. Mondesi, who is on the
15-day disabled list because of the injury, traveled to Coral
Gables on Tuesday to seek the opinion of Dr. Jose Uriebe. Mondesi
was originally checked by Dr. Allan Gross in Toronto, and also by
Dr. Frank Jobe in Los Angeles. Jobe told him to rest the elbow
completely.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: 2B Jose Ortiz figures to make his first big league
start against a left-handed pitcher when the A's travel to Chicago
for a weekend series. Ortiz was recalled on Tuesday after leading
the Pacific Coast League with 148 hits. ''I don't want him to think
this is something big,'' said A's manager Art Howe. ''We brought
him up to face left-handed pitchers.'' Ortiz says he's ready for
the challenge. ''I think I can help a little bit with my offense,''
he said. ... RHP Omar Olivares was scheduled to make his second
rehab start Wednesday at Class-A Modesto. He's slated to throw four
innings. ... Entering Wednesday's game, A's starters have gone at
least seven innings in each of the last seven games. That's the
longest such streak since July 12-18, 1990. The A's are 31-11 this
year when the starters go at least seven innings.
