<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minikus Leads in Equestrian Trials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, Calif. (AP) -- Todd Minikus, riding Oh Star,
was the only rider to leave all 16 jumps standing Wednesday and
moved into first place in the U.S. Equestrian Team Olympic show
jumping trials.
</P>
<P>
   Minikus, of Loxahatchee, Fla., moved past Laura Kraut, of
Oconomowac, Wis., who held a 3.75-penalty lead after the first set
of trials in June.
</P>
<P>
   Her mount, Liberty, dropped two rails on the impressive course
at the Oaks/Blenheim Rancho Mission Viejo Riding Park.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm obviously disappointed,'' said Kraut, the 1992 Olympic
alternate. ''Both of us were a little rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Minikus now has an 0.5-penalty lead after being the only one the
11 competitors to have a trip.
</P>
<P>
   The best American finisher at the April World Cup finals, where
he tied for sixth, Minikus, 38, is one of the favorites to make the
four-person U.S. Equestrian Team that will compete in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   He was tied for fifth after the first set of trials with Alison
Firestone, who was No. 1 in the U.S. Equestrian Team's computer
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone, however, withdrew last month after her mount, Jox,
developed an abscess that could not be cleared up in time for the
trials, which continue Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Margie Goldstein-Engle, 42, of Wellington, Fla., and Nona
Garson, 40, of Tewksbury, N.J., held on to third and fourth place
by scoring just one knockdown each. With only 4.5 penalties
separating the top six, the makeup of the team is still very much
up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything could happen, certainly,'' Garson said. ''We've got a
great group here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
