<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Indians Seek Congress End  </HEADLINE>
By GONZALO SOLANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- About 1,500 Indians, students and labor
unionists marched in Quito Wednesday, demanding a referendum that
could lead to the dissolution of Congress and halt the switch to a
U.S.-dollar economy.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Antonio Vargas, head of the powerful Confederation of
Indigenous Nations of Ecuador, the banner-waving demonstrators
delivered petitions that organizers said contained some 1.5 million
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ecuadorean law, a minimum of 600,000 signatures are
required for any group of citizens to request a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas warned that if authorities are ''intelligent, they should
accept a popular consultation.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' Indian movement has been at odds with President Gustavo
Noboa's government for months. In January, Vargas led an Indian
uprising with military backing that prompted the ouster of Noboa's
predecessor, President Jamil Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has shown signs of turning around under Noboa, whose
approval ratings remain steady at around 40 percent. And
demonstration called by Indians and leftist-led labor federations
in recent months have been marked by low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa has largely carried on with Mahuad's economic programs,
including a plan to phase out the local currency, the sucre, and
replace it with the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The government hopes the currency changeover will stabilize the
economy, promote business investment and end inflation topping 100
percent a year, the highest in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to completely eliminate the sucre by
September.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue the dollar plan will hurt the poor by causing
prices to rise to international levels. Currently many basic food
products and services are subsidized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2317 </TRAILER>
