<DOCNO> APW20000802.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer's Exclusion Claim Is Heard  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT STODDARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- An international board of arbitrators met Thursday
to hear the final arguments in a suit by Suzu Chiba, one of Japan's
top swimmers, who claims she was unfairly left off her country's
team for the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the first of its kind raised by a Japanese athlete,
and has focused intense scrutiny on the often opaque selection
process used to decide who represents Japan at Olympic
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Chiba is a two-time Olympian, winner of Japan's 200-meter
freestyle swimming championship and holder of the world's
second-fastest time in the 100-meter freestyle last year.
</P>
<P>
   She was left off the Olympic roster, however, because swimming
officials claimed she was not up to world-class competition. Chiba
then sued the Japan Amateur Swimming Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss-based Court of Arbitration for Sports began hearing
testimony from her and sports officials in Tokyo on Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Questions have been raised about other Olympic team choices as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Harumi Hiroyama was left off the marathon team for Sydney, even
though she had a better time than one of the athletes selected.
Hiroyama qualified instead for the 10,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Chiba would seem to have a strong case.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Chiba finished 10th in the 200 freestyle and was
13th in the 400, behind compatriot Eri Yamanoi, who was seventh.
</P>
<P>
   After the Atlanta Games she restarted her career under Bud
McAllister, who coached gold medalist Janet Evans of the United
States. Her time of 54.99 seconds in the 100 freestyle last year
was the second-best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Then she won the 200 freestyle at Japan's national championships
in April -- a key event in selecting members for the Olympic team.
Her time of 2 minutes, 0.54 seconds was better than the Olympic
qualifying standard of 2:01.02.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese women broke 22 national records and one world record --
the first time Japan has set a world record in 28 years -- at the
April meet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-02-00 2326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000802.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Convention Nominates Bush  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Republicans awarded Texas Gov. George W.
Bush their 2000 presidential nomination Wednesday night and chanted
in unison as running mate Dick Cheney ignited the convention with a
partisan spark, taunting the Democrats: ''It's time for them to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his vice presidential nomination, Cheney said Al Gore
is ''trying to separate himself from Bill Clinton's shadow, but it
won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somehow we will never see one without thinking of the other,''
he said in a speech that drew waves of applause from Republicans
locked out of the White House for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush watched from his hotel suite a few miles away as his
nomination -- won in the hard primary battles of winter -- was sealed
by acclamation on a warm summer night. He called the convention
vote ''the stamp,'' on his campaign, ''the formal moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing himself as a ''tough competitor,'' the Texas
governor, son of a president and self-described ''compassionate
conservative,'' asserted: ''I'm going to give it my best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention hall at the First Union Arena, 2,066
delegates erupted as Bush's nomination was announced, cheering and
waving placards that bore the name of their ticket. Confetti
streamed from the ceiling; beach balls bobbed across a packed
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney pledged immediate change in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the first hour of the first day ... he will restore decency
and integrity to the Oval Office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former congressman and Defense Secretary, Cheney was the main
speaker on an evening that marked his return to politics after
eight years in private life, most recently as CEO of the oil
industry firm, Halliburton Co.
</P>
<P>
   The evening session beganon a somber note. Former football
quarterback Steve Young, delivering the invocation, asked a special
blessing for the recovery of former President Gerald R. Ford,
hospitalized a few miles away after suffering two small strokes.
His doctor said the 87-year-old Ford, honored at Tuesday night's
convention session, appeared to suffer no brain damage or permanent
disability and that chances for a full recovery were good.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also heard from The Rock of the World Wrestling
Federation. In what passed for controversy at a harmonious party
gathering, some conservatives felt he was too violent a figure to
appear on the GOP program. But his message was conventional enough
-- an appeal to his fans to register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday, Republican speakers had barely tagged Gore in
convention sessions designed to appeal to swing voters. But that
all ended quickly when Cheney strode to the podium to deliver his
debut speech as Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Moving quickly to the point, he said the Clinton-Gore era was
one of ''opportunities squandered,'' and noted that Clinton had
vowed to hold power until the last moment. ''That is his right,''
he said. ''But my friends, that last hour is coming. That last day
is near,'' he added to thunderous applause.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wheel has turned,'' said Cheney. ''And it is time... It is
time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times he said it was ''time for them to go,'' and GOP
partisans took up the chant, jerking their thumbs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The barb was an echo of Al Gore's vice presidential speech
before the Democratic convention in 1992, aimed then at President
George Bush, father of the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   When Wyoming cast the vote that put Gov. Bush over the top,
friends and family watching TV with the nominee burst into
applause. He flashed a smile of satisfaction, then kissed his wife
Laura on the cheek. She grabbed his right hand with both of her
hands and squeezed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge honor ... a major step toward becoming the
president of the United States,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney lauded Bush in words that implicitly criticized Clinton.
Bush, he said, ''is a man without pretense and cynicism. A man of
principle, a man of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's nomination preceded Bush's by about an hour in a
convention schedule that mostly ran like clockwork. A few states
dawdled before casting their votes, and were promptly prodded to
hurry up.
</P>
<P>
   The political hoopla capped a day in which Bush flew into the
convention city aboard a campaign plane repainted red white and
blue. He campaigned energetically in English and Spanish, and
assured supporters, ''Together we can win in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days of relentlessly upbeat convention oratory aimed at
voters in the middle of the political spectrum were apparently
paying off for Bush. Polling by Voter.com-Battleground showed
support for the GOP ticket rising from 8 points over the weekend to
13 points through Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates usually get a ''bounce'' from their
convention, and Gore will have a chance to reverse the GOP trend
when he announces his choice for running mate Aug. 8 and opens his
convention Aug. 14 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the two-term governor of Texas who campaigned as
''compassionate conservative,'' stood as leader of a party that was
as unified as at any time since Ronald Reagan's re-election
campaign in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
