<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actors Begin To Fast in Ad Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five actors have started a fast to publicize
their cause in the 14-week-old strike against the advertising
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about martyrdom or starvation, it's about
education and inspiration for all members of the union,'' said
James Arone, a member of the Screen Actors Guild.
</P>
<P>
   Arone and four other union members will not eat solid foods
during the fast, although other union members may replace them in
the protest. The fast will continue until a contract agreement is
reached, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They see no other way to resolve this,'' strike coordinator
Michael Brennan said on behalf of the SAG and the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   A call to advertising industry representatives was not
immediately returned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The strike already is the longest commercial actors strike in
union history, and an effort to restart talks last month was
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Actors want to be paid residuals for ads on cable television, as
they are now paid for network spots, and also want jurisdiction
over commercials shot for the Internet. Advertisers are seeking to
pay actors a flat fee for all commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has cost the Los Angeles County economy $70 million
in lost wages and support services, according to county economic
experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
